reviewText: ...it gets the job done. Lets face it, many of the stunts pulled in this film are far fetched. Technically they might work, but in a seat of your pants, gun to the head, package to the wall scenario, not likely. That's why it's a movie. Again, Liam Neesom holds his own, plugging away with a solid heart and fists of iron.This time around mom and dad are kidnapped and daughter Kimy is much wiser for the wear, effectively carrying out dads detailed and edgy plans for survival. Istanbul is the locale which doesn't add much atmosphere to the harrowing chases yet it still helps give a desperate gloominess to the film. Many people liked the first film and this time around the idea was to touch on the original elements, then quickly set up a premise that makes diving into the action an easy transition.I got the same thrilling "hows this gonna work out" feel I got from the first Taken and thats okay with me. Taken 2 is fun and exciting escapism that you can't look at with too critical an eye. Basically, enjoy the ride.

reviewText: This movie nearly, but not quite, attains the status of accidental satire. The script is so absolutely dire - based on the classic five-second pitch "hey, what if this time round the parents are the ones who get taken and the kid has to save them?" - that you want everyone to die within the first ten minutes just to get it all over with. Alas, this doesn't happen and so Neeson - a decent actor who deserves much better scripts, roles, and everything else than this - ponderously plods his way through one inept plot device to the next. There's one genuinely accidentally funny line when the Neeson character tells his daughter, who's in an expensive hotel room in downtown Istanbul, via a mini phone "Take a grenade. Remove the pin. Now, throw it somewhere safe."Aside from that one brief moment, the rest of the movie is so turgid, so absolutely lacking in imagination, pacing, drama, and everything else that it is quite impossible to understand why the crew bothered to show up each day to make the movie - unless the crew were Turkish and didn't speak English and therefore didn't understand just how truly bad this pathetic movie-by-numbers is.Avoid at all costs unless you're desperately insomniac.
summary: Not Quite Bad Enough to be Funny

reviewText: Even though I enjoyed watching Taken 2 tonight, the truth is it's *extremely* similar to the first Taken.  Only because I'm such a huge fan of high octane action films such as this one will I give in and award the movie 4 stars.  It's realistically more like a 3-star film.  Anyway it stars the always talented Liam Neeson doing exactly what he did in the first Taken- chasing bad guys around with guns and his fists, and specifically and strategically planning the best ways to instruct his daughter to avoid being captured by the kidnappers.  Liam's daughter and wife play larger roles in the storyline this time around (at least the daughter does- the wife is basically spending her time being a helpless captured victim).I have to be honest.  Even though Liam coming up with these carefully planned directions to either guide his daughter to safety or help him escape where he's being held/captured, I have to laugh at how unrealistically sharp and skilled he is at his technique.  It's unintentionally really funny to me how he never misses a beat when explaining what to do and where to go.  I wasn't laughing in the first movie when Liam did the same thing perhaps due to his character being really believable and just plain good, but now it seems really funny for some reason.  Probably means Taken wasn't meant to have a sequel and segments such as these weren't meant to occur ever again.  That way we could preserve the greatness of the original Taken and recognize it as one of Liam's highest achievements as an actor.  The sequel kind of ruins what made the first one so great.What seems particularly odd about Taken 2 however, is all the storyline segments concerning Liam's daughter.  She doesn't want to drive, she doesn't have the confidence to pass her driving test, and she doesn't believe she's good enough at parellel parking, however all these issues magically go away just as soon as she's forced to speed away from the gun-carrying kidnappers.  Suddenly her driving abilities improve dramatically (with a couple exceptions).  It's odd writing.  It's almost like her driving problems never should have been included in the script and were only included because the writers couldn't think of another way to make her character memorable.  Also, it's hilarious that she doesn't hesitate to pull pins from grenades and toss them across the street (a fairly clever piece of writing here, though probably not realistic but I could be wrong- you'll see why when you watch the movie).  Basically Liam is using the sound and the amount of seconds that passes after the grenade explosion to figure out where he's being captured.  His daughter is able execute these instructions without feeling any fear which is odd.This movie is also a victim of camera jerking during the action scenes, which means when Liam is running around beating people up, we don't really see it- all we see is the camera jerking all over the place.  I can't recall if the originl was guilty of this same noticeable flaw.  I strongly dislike when movies ruin the action scenes with quick camera movements.  Also the writing in several spots is incredibly cliched.  Of *course* Liam doesn't approve of his daughter's new boyfriend, and the boyfriend acts exactly as you'd expect- very confident, willing to shake hands, willing to present himself as a perfect gentlement.  Meh.  The original Taken was too good to resort to this kind of boring and obvious writing.  I'd expect the same out of the sequel.Overall, Taken is a highly exaggerated but ultimately disappointing sequel.  I really should give it 3 stars but... I can't, because it was entertaining.  Sigh, haha.

reviewText: "Taken" was, to me, the movie that threw Liam Neeson into the "action star" category. I know he was a Jedi knight at one point, but that was the movie that made it real. The story was compelling, the action amazing, and the entire thing was a thrill ride. While the story this time out is very unique (the relatives of some of the men he killed in the first film are out for revenge) and I loved where it came from, the execution of the whole thing faltered horribly.While "Taken 2" will not let you lose faith in Liam Neeson's ability to kill a man creatively with his bare hands, the director this time out seems to take it as a personal challenge to change camera angles as many times as humanly possible during any action sequence. As a result, any time Liam is talking to someone, it's all calm and steady. The instant he moves toward a person to attack, the director takes the movie into an angle frenzy that lets you know there's a lot of action going on, but you'll never know what it is. It looks as if they didn't want to bother choreographing the fight scenes, so instead they just had Liam jerk around a bit and threw the camera into all sort of close-ups of elbows, shirts, fists, and such with sound effects. During a car chase scene, I counted 65 different camera angle changes in one minute, some lasting just a half a second close-up of a steering wheel, foot on the gas, etc. It's deplorable. At one point, Liam puts his hand on a guy's face and the guy dies, making it appear Liam killed him by sheer willpower. I am all for another one in this franchise (and they easily pave the way for a sequel at the end), but get a better director the next time out.
summary: A great story but horrible directing

reviewText: If you like infantile macho power fantasies like Batman and GI Joe but don't think they take themselves seriously enough, then Taken 2 is for you! Liam Neeson stars as a paternalistic old white guy who massacres reams of treacherous brown people to protect his helpless, emotional womenfolk. It's even better than the stories I come up with when I play with my AR-15 in the bathtub! (And while I watch Taken 2, mom doesn't nag me to wash behind my ears. I SAID DON'T TREAD ON ME, MOM!)It does have its weak points, though. For example, sometimes the women talk. Also, a fair number of people in the background of some scenes got away without so much as an elbow to the throat (what kind of message is that sending to our children???). And worst of all the action scenes are shot like an abstract European art film, asking you to ponder random blurry shots of elbows and the backs of heads as they fly through the frame. It's almost as if they're trying to get us to reflect on our increasingly dull familiarity with violence; the scenes blur into an incomprehensible flurry of meaningless carnage individually as well as collectively, leading the viewer to ask, "why?" But I guess I should have known they'd try to brainwash me into thinking about stuff: the director's from FR*NCE.And speaking of things that are for snobs, there are SUBTITLES in this movie. Just shoot him in the foot seven times already, movie, jeez louise! Yeahhh, like that. Now impale him on something. Zoom in close! Yeahhhhhhhh. Push it in there with your big, strong hands. reviewText: The main plot idea was perfectly reasonable if not a little predicable.  Shortly after Taken 1 the family of the Albanian mobsters that were previously killed go out for revenge and this time the whole family is involved.  It was a mindless action flick, and I wasn't bored while watching it.  Unfortunately this sequel lacked a lot of what made the first one good enough to warrant a sequel in the first place.Firstly, I found the settings very limited.  Where the first movie felt like it ranged all over Paris, with LN having to work for every clue, this one just had LN chasing someone down one dirty ally or hallway after another.  The action scenes also followed the recent trend of shaking the camera like a martini and shooting disjointed and unrelated things to add a sense of action, then over-using jump cuts to splice the mess back together.A lot of the plot specifics didn't add up or were too convenient to be believable.  I won't ruin it by running them down specifically here.  Let's just say that unless you think a teenager can drive a cab though barricades and several 50 caliber machine guns to break into a US embassy, an LA girl struggling for normalcy that just narrowly escaped sex-slavery in France will want to travel to Istanbul to "get away", or villains will always do the cliche "I'm just going to leave you alone now in a locked room by yourself even though I know you've single-handily killed all my previous men" then you might have plot issues with this movie too.One last nit-pick...who ever directed the lighting of this movie must have thought all of Istanbul uses cheap, dim, green-casting florescent lights inside.Other than all that LN and FJ were good as always, and it was nice FJ had a bigger role in this one.  I just wish I had waiting for the rental to be cheaper or to go free/prime before I watched it, and unlike the first one, I probably won't be watching this one again ever.

reviewText: There are two types of sequels in Hollywood - the ones that get made because there's more story to tell and the ones that get made because the first film made a lot of money. At first Taken seemed like it was getting a sequel because it made a bunch of money - but in fact Taken 2 had a good enough idea behind it that I felt there was easily more good story to be told. With the premise of the families of the bad guys in the first film going on an offensive to get back at Bryan Mills was excellent! This premise gives both sides of the conflict the same motivation of protecting their families - which is universal and pretty cool for an action film premise.The problem is with Mills' entire family in peril - the director keeps the viewer in touch with the family throughout - so we lose that sense of urgency that the first film provided. In the first film we don't see his daughter after she's kidnapped - and it's intense throughout the film because we don't know what's happening to his daughter. This lack of suspense really takes one of the best elements that made the first film such a hit and replaces it with action sequences which suffer due to the lack of urgency and suspense. It's a big problem - there should've been another element added to replace the lack of suspense problem - as just action cannot fix this.FYI - This paragraph has nothing to do with the movie itself. I think - the bad guys should've just hired another assassin to get Mills and have it become more of a Die Hard, Bourne film cat and mouse game between Mills and an equally talented bad guy. We would've known Mills could win - but since we hadn't already seen him succeed in this kidnap scenario before the intensity needed to be amped up in a different way by taking Mills out of his element a bit. They need someone who can challenge Bryan Mills' level of preparedness so the viewer could feel like they are seeing something worth the "certain set of skills" Mills has.Anyway - the action was good (not great) Luc Besson knows how to orchestrate a good action film and Olivier Megaton is a solid director for action films - the pacing felt a little stop-start but it wasn't egregious. Overall the film lacked what could've been a great sequel based on the story needing to be expanded and made it feel like a sequel that was out for more cash.The bar was set high - by surprisingly excellent action romp that was Taken and Taken 2 (like many Eastern European thugs) got its head bashed into the bar by Liam Neeson.
summary: I will hunt you down (again) and I will kill you (again)

reviewText: 2008's TAKEN was a breath of fresh air: an action film that didn't take itself too seriously, but at the same time wasn't necessarily an homage or parody.  It presented Liam Neeson as an unlikely action hero: where he had previously seemed tall and gangly, now he was broad-shouldered and menacing, a force to be reckoned with.  And thanks to Neeson's charisma, his everyman Bryan Mills shined brightly enough to eclipse any non-PC ethics his role may have raised (Daddy is always right, and little girls should not go abroad without male protection).Well, if you liked TAKEN, you'll like TAKEN 2...because it's basically the exact same thing.  Minus a star for originality; let's face it, that's a given.  Minus half a star for a rather uninteresting premise: the father of one of the victims from the first film decides to kidnap Mills's family in revenge.  He gets Mills and his ex Lenore (Famke Janssen, returning); however, he misses daughter Kim (Maggie Grace, also back), and as such he underestimates how some traits run in the family.  When Mills gets free (come on, you know he does) , he races the clock to retrieve his wife and dispense justice...or vengeance.  The film doesn't care what you call it.Sound skeptical?  Well of course it is.  TAKEN required you to suspend your disbelief for a while, and just accept the fact that Mills had "a certain set of skills" that gave him Godlike powers.  TAKEN 2 asks you to throw your disbelief out the window and just go with it.  And you do, largely because Maggie Grace is given a lot more screen time; she goes from being the victim to a real player, a strong female role that the series desperately needed.  Neeson is still in fine form, of course; never doubt his screen presence.  It's the wholly implausible script, and frantic direction, that ultimately bog the film down.  However, for fans of the first, TAKEN 2 is a nice addition.  Perhaps not required viewing, but damned if it isn't a decent thrill ride.
summary: 3.5 Stars: It's the exact same thing...which isn't a bad thing.

reviewText: One hopes for a return of a great story when they make a sequel. It doesn't happen here.All the actors are back except for the rich husband who is now breaking up with Bryan Miles' (Liam Neeson) ex-wife, played by Famke Janssen. Miles suggests she and the daughter played by Maggie Grace join him in Istanbul after his little security gig is over. Of course, neither of them learned their lesson about staying home the first time and they surprise daddy in Istanbul so this plot can continue.Sure enough they are followed, chased, fight and are captured i.e. Liam and Famke are caught by the family and extended family of the evil pandering, slave-trading, corrupt no-goodniks from Tripolie (pron. Tri-pool-ya), Albania who he killed in Paris in the first film. They manage to find out who he was by beating the French cop, and then by paying off someone in Tirana to find out where he was. As luck would have it, just over the border.With a secret cell phone, Neeson manages to call his daughter who is hiding in the hotel from her would-be captors. She refuses to save herself and bravely states: "I can do this, Dad."A 10th grader could have written a better story which held no surprises, hokey dialogue and implausible scenes like Liam talking to his daughter on his cell phone while he has a gun on someone and they have guns on him and his ex. They just stand there! Even the Krav Maga and Hapkido scenes were hard to follow and that 50 caliber machine gun would have split that car down the middle faster than a buzz saw.You might ask several questions, as I did. How did someone in Tirana know that Bryan Miles would be in Istanbul? How did his captors not find the mini-cell phone? Why were their captors leaving them there tied up, to marinate? How come his ex-wife didn't scream at him at the end for asking her to join him in Turkey? How come this director wasn't traded to the Albanians for some future player to be named later?This movie needs massive resuscitation. Only Liam's acting skill and his ability to portray a loving tender father and ex-husband while schizophrenically opening a severe can of whupas give this film a faint heartbeat.My advice is to stay away from Taken 2 or you will be had.
summary: Stay Away From Taken 2 or You Will Be Had

reviewText: TAKEN 2 (Dir. Olivier Megaton, and I'm not kidding, 2012, 93 minutes) was fun for me to watch, tough to review because it's a mindless "actioner" serving only to showcase Liam Neeson's immensely likeable talents. That man can go from playing Oskar Schindler to performing better than Steven Seagal ever did, as he does here.Neeson returns as CIA security field agent Bryan Mills, this time convincing his ex-wife and daughter to accompany him to Istanbul. They refuse at first - that is only wise - yet in Istanbul suddenly, there they are! Surprise, dad!! What kind of evil international hoodlums are you going to kill for us this time?! In this case, it is the crazy father of one of the men Neeson killed in the original 2008 film.So of course the film spirals down from that point. As I said, the director makes this a fun film. The cinematography is not bad, making Neeson look exactly like a killing machine yet his own skills add to that crisp editing. The man fights better than Seagal on film, and sadly the editing gets too crisp with some of his fight scenes merely a hint and not shown. Too many car chases in Istanbul ... how I hate car chases. These have no style to them, but at least they're over rapidly.The film has a snappy, rapid-fire approach to the violence and its only real redeeming quality is Neeson. It is rushed, illogical, nearly brainless: a typical popcorn film and I enjoyed it as such. It has nowhere near the stunning panache or the skill of the originalTaken(see my review).As it is, it seems both films were virtually ignored. In fact, the original TAKEN, a remake of Steven Seagal'sBelly of the Beast, convinced me that they should have made Neeson the next James Bond and Spielberg ought to have kept him on to play LINCOLN.This has the talents of returning stars Jon Gries (another great perennial favorite of mine), Famke Janssen and Maggie Grace. As for the rest, it's take-it-or-leave-it 'international violence'. But I love nearly anything Neeson does, and I certainly enjoyed this dumb, all-action "CIA family" film with its Goth soundtrack - done so brilliantly in the original film - and its careful shadings of color, light and darkness. It's a lot of work for what ended up appearing to be a direct-to-video mediocrity!
summary: Minus a star for mediocrity that took nearly 5 years to accomplish

reviewText: Liam Neeson is a complete badass.  How do you define a 'badass'?  Well, typically all you'd need to do is look at a picture of Chuck Norris and you'd instantly understand.  But, some things change and clearly Liam Neeson is taking over the Hollywood action scene.  If you need evidence, just watch any of his recent films.  What's that?  You hated The Phantom Menace, but Liam Neeson was still a badass?  Absolutely.  He lightsaber duels with the Sith, he kills man-eating wolves, he battles aliens on the ocean - and yes, he even takes time to beat the crap out of common criminals in Taken.This time, Neeson returns in Taken 2 as Bryan Mills, a former intelligence agent that does security jobs on the side, while trying to maintain a healthy relationship as an over-protective father with his daughter, Kim (Maggie Grace).  Rade rbedzija plays the film's villain, Murad Hoxha, an Albania mobster that is seeking revenge for the death of son (one of the countless thugs Neeson killed in the first film).  Famke Janssen also returns as Lenore, Bryan's ex-wife, who just happens to have recently separated with her most recent husband - naturally prompting a Neeson/Janssen reunion.If you're looking for a movie with drama or basically any kind of plot-driven substance, this film isn't really for you.  All you really need to do is see the film's trailer and you'll quickly understand how this film is going to go.  Neeson's character and his wife are abducted and it's up to their daughter to help free them.  It's pretty cut and dry, meaning the film is completely predictable from beginning to end.  However, if you judge the film on that merit, you'll hate it and most likely not even spend your money to see it.  The point of this film (and most any film) is to be entertained - by a watered-down James Bond - who's only mission is to retrieve his family, while beat up the bad guys on his way.Overall, if you're a fan of the first Taken, then you'll definitely want to see the sequel.  Same actors, same action, same premise, etc.  It's a quick 90 minutes, so don't even bother checking the time.  It will be over before you know it, and once you're engaged with all the excitement that this film has to offer, you'll be begging for the next sequel.  And, by all means - bring it on!Film Grade: BThe Friday Night Date Night ReviewFacebook.com/FNDNReview

reviewText: The original "Taken" was a fast paced, riveting revenge flick that offered brief entertainment, provided you could look past its bizarre flaws (the primary one being a rather racist tone). This sequel contains some of what made the first movie good- Liam Neeson is a hardcore BA, conveying a sense of authentic, lethal ability that is achieved through wisdom and experience, as opposed to high flying kicks and theatrics. All of his combat techniques are ugly, as opposed to being choreographed for beauty, and therefore feel grounded in reality. Neeson's performance is quite good, for the most part, though even he can't erase some particularly bad lines of dialogue that were written for him (a tradition that was established in the original "Taken").This movie could have succeeded, but it suffers from a plot that is so disjointed, it's downright weird. It's almost as if the writers were just phoning it in on this one, so as to have the means to create another revenge movie. Nothing wrong with that, necessarily, but it's so disjointed, it almost feels surreal... like the characters are stumbling around in a dream. "Taken 2" offers some moderate entertainment for an hour and a half, benefiting from some decent action sequences and the presence of Neeson, but it ultimately proves forgettable. It is, unfortunately, a pale imitator of the original, and watching it only made me wish that I had spent that time watching the first "Taken" again, or something else entirely.
summary: Disjointed and lacking the punch of its predecessor

reviewText: Taken 2 is the follow-up to 2008's Taken number 1, which I bet you had no idea about. But it's true! Taken 2 is the long-awaited sequel to Taken number 1, and it proves yet again that Liam Neeson is so much more than a guy who saved some Jews in some black and white movie from a really long time ago. It proves that Liam Neeson is still an extremely viable and sought-after action movie star...you know, when more popular action stars like Michael Biehn, Dolph Lundgren and Lassie are busy with other projects.In this installment of Taken, Liam Neeson, Maggie Graceless and Famke Johanssen are all able to reunite and have some family time in Istanbul (which is a peace-loving, Muslim city that used to be called Constantinople), which is downright offensive when you consider that Maggie Graceless is still playing a teenager at the age of 30 and that Famke Johanssen is way too old to pretend that she was ever Jean Grey or a Bond "girl." Anyhoo, though, reunite they do, and just when Neeson's character and Johanssen's character are about to, shall we say, fornicate in a quickie right before they have to take Maggie Graceless' character to the vet, the bad guys from Taken number 1 burst into the room, ending the anticipated sexual encounter.However, they take Famke Johannsen's character hostage and sell Maggie Graceless' character into white slavery. The movie then ends rather abruptly after some clichéd, action-movie developments: First, Michael Biehn, Dolph Lundgren and Lassie all make surprise cameos, which really interrupted the flow of the high-stakes drama in my opinion. Then, Neeson's character finally succeeds in saving both Famke Johannsen's and Maggie Graceless' characters, but, being women, they both get angry with him for "taking too long" to finally save them, and they slap him aggressively across the face for his efforts. Finally, in what I can only judge as a totally tasteless move by the director, Liam Neeson's dead wife, Natasha Richardson, is actually shown over and over again throughout the closing credits of the movie, which utterly failed to satisfy the director's apparent desire to have some kind of closure in the movie's plot.Despite these problems, I can't wait to buy Taken 2 when it is released on VHS soon. In fact, me and my friends will have a sleepover party to celebrate when Taken 2 is finally available on home video. In the meantime, just disregard the extremely negative reviews of Taken 2 on sites such as Rotten Tomatoes because just because everyone says this movie s/u/c/k/s does not mean there is a consensus on this movie's s/u/c/k/in/g.
summary: Liam Neesen has..."Taken" me to new levels of Awesomeness!

reviewText: TAKEN released in 2008 was a tightly woven thriller that boosted Liam Neeson's already burgeoning career: he was a killer's killer and managed to garner acclaim from critics and audiences alike.  Now we have a sequel (and there may be more, as the end of the film suggests) that just isn't up to the same standard as the original, but for those who saw Part 1, then Part 2 will likely not disappoint.The film opens in Albania where the old father Murad Krasniqi (Rade Serbedzija) is burying his son and some villagers killed by Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson) and he vows revenge. Switch to Los Angles where we see Bryan and his ex-wife Lenore (Famke Janssen), who is recuperating from her second divorce, and their daughter Kim (Maggie Grace) who is entering her first relationship with Jamie (a promising Luke Grimes) arguing over priorities.  Bryan still loves Kim and Lenore and when Lenore tearfully confesses her frustration that her plans to take Kim to China to regroup emotionally have fallen through, Bryan announces he has a job in Istanbul, Turkey - 3 days worth - and invites them to join him after his job is complete.But of course in Istanbul Bryan's mission involves offing all the people from the Albanian crew and when Lenore and Kim arrive the family is re-bonded until Murad directs that all three be captured and killed. From there it is the predictable cat and mouse games of capture/escape/killing by every means possible/ car chases action and the few who are left in the end make a pact of sorts...and more need not be said.Oliver Megaton directs a screenplay by Luc Besson and Robert Mark Kamen. One of the glories of the film is the opportunity to see the many sites of Istanbul. This is not a bad film at all - it is just not up to the standard of the original even thought he players are the same.  Grady Harp, April 13

reviewText: I really wanted to love this movie.  The first Taken was super, and I've been wanting more in the same vein from Liam Neeson since then.  I was happy when Taken 2 finally came out on DVD and ordered it right away, even after reading the negative reviews.  So, it just arrived and I've watched it for the first time.I'm disappointed and angry at the director.  I think he had a poor concept of what the end result of his decisions would look like.  The super-fast camera angle changes during fights in particular were a big mistake.  In fact, I can't think of anything he did right.The acting is great, of course.  The whole cast is superb.  Actually, everything about this movie is first-rate, except for the directing, and if I were rating based on that alone, I would have to give it a 1 since that's the lowest Amazon rating.I don't regret buying it, but I wish I'd waited until the price went down some.  I got it at $14.95, and the price will drop, probably pretty quickly, when the distributors realize they'll have to drop their price in order to sell all their stock.So, buyer beware.  This movie is not nearly as good as the first one.  It's worth owning if you really enjoy watching Liam Neeson take out bad guys and be a hero.  But read the reviews that detail all the bad points about the directing and believe them.  If you still want to own it, as I did, and if like me, you haven't seen it yet, then at least you'll not be unaware when you watch it for the first time.  My recommendation, though, is to rent it first, and decide for yourself how much you like it.  I didn't rent it first because I'm that much of a Liam Neeson fan.

reviewText: When will people learn not to take Liam Neeson's stuff? TAKEN 2 addresses one of the more nagging recurring plot holes in storytelling: What happens when the hero doesn't dispose of all the villains? The sequel opens in Albania with the burial ceremony of those sex-traffickers Bryan Mills (Neeson) had mowed thru in the first film. And there's the terrifying patriarch Murad Krasniqi (Rade Sherbedgia) presiding over their graves and vowing bloody revenge.Cut to Los Angeles, some time later. Ex-CIA operative Bryan Mills still can't help being over-protective of his daughter Kim (Maggie Grace), which sucks for her new boyfriend. For her part, Kim is still traumatized over her harrowing abduction from around a year ago. While we were away, Mills and his estranged ex-wife Lenore (Famke Jannsen) had achieved a sort of détente. And when a distraught Lenore admits that her current marriage is speedily crumbling, to try to make her feel better, Mills invites her and Kim to holiday with him in Istanbul where he'll be conducting some security consultant work. Note that Istanbul is practically a stone's throw away from Albania. This is what's known as a foreshadowing observation.At age one hundred and four Liam Neeson still demonstrates fantastic action chops. He generates such gravitas, his performance has such credibility, you just buy that he's perfectly capable of extricating himself from any form of tight scrape. In Istanbul, Krasniqi marshals his forces and strikes, and yet Mills is canny enough to put gum in the works. He and his wife are taken but, thanks to his timely warning, Kim escapes, if barely. We now arrive at the best segment of the film, when a captured Mills, over a phone he'd secreted away, manages to talk Kim thru the intricate process of determining his unknown location. I won't say much more than that, other than the process involves a shoelace, a map, and grenades. What follows is a nifty sequence that equally illustrates Kim's gumption and vulnerability. It allows Maggie Grace to step out of her thankless role of victim. You may have to be generous in overlooking the ridiculous stuff she gets up to in following her dad's orders.Again, the lesson to take away here is "Do not take Liam Neeson's stuff!" After the box office success of this sequel there's already talk of a third picture, and I'm down with that. But only if Neeson is a participant. Yes, the sheen brought about by an aged Neeson kicking butt has worn off some, but there's still enough of that luster to make TAKEN 2 a satisfying watch. He abuses more Albanians in this film franchise than Peter Falk ever did in TUNE IN TOMORROW. It's a slick thriller, maybe not a deep one, and it fails to retain the shock value of the first film. It certainly doesn't have anything as memorable as Neeson's awesome "I will find you" speech. But I like the in-jokes referencing the first film. And the acting is across-the-board solid, with Rade Sherbedgia making a perfectly hissable big bad. You know he means deadly business when he bluntly informs Famke: "Mrs. Mills, you are a good mother and a brave woman. For that I am going to send you back home... piece by piece." Oh, yeah, he's a perfect candidate for Liam Neeson's brand of brutal efficiency. After all, he took Liam's stuff. Dude. Must. Pay.3.5 out of 5 stars.

reviewText: So, what do you get when you give an enormous budget, superstar actors, and no oversight to a pretentious, self-important, ex-graffiti artist turned movie maker, who has no sense of timing, spacial relations, or how to frame a shot?Well, you get Taken 2. Holy cow, what a mess. Given a different director and a slight re-write this movie would have been fantastic. There was so much there to work with, but the director had no idea what he was doing. My wife and I had to rewind almost every other scene because you couldn't tell where people were, what they were doing, or how they did it. The climax of the movie looked like Liam Neeson killed a guy by gently shoving his face. What?! After two rewinds we FINALLY saw that he had been impaled on something that was barely in the frame and you can't see until you look at it very carefully. We love action movies and we don't need to be spoon fed a narrative, but it REALLY helps when the shots actually show you what the heck is going on.And on that note, hey, Oliver "Megaton" Fontana! It's called "Shaky" cam, not "Donkey With Restless Leg Syndrome Is Kicking the Camera" cam. And quick zooms don't work if that's all you do for two hours and the framing NEVER focuses on the subjects. Seriously, this guy would start already partially zoomed in to frame a character and then he would quick zoom so fast that the camera couldn't find the actor for 3-4 seconds, all the while we're looking at a car bumper or a blank wall. And when your shots only LAST 4 seconds max, that's an eternity of time in which we can't watch a movie because this guy obviously doesn't know how photography works. I did a count with about 30 minutes to go in the movie and I gave up after 10 minutes because there was exactly ONE scene in which he kept a shot going for longer than 3 seconds. Most of the shots only lasted half a second and then we're slammed into another angle, camera gyrating wildly, and then before we can focus, WHACK, we're in yet another shot. It's called pacing, "Megaton". This guy shouldn't be hired to do anything other than music videos or McDonalds ads. Then his complete lack of a clue wouldn't be as noticeable. This isn't a style, it's a desperate bid to use a camera technique to hide incompetence.A quick word about the director's name. He calls himself Oliver Megaton. His real name is Oliver Fontana. If you have the arrogance to name yourself after a measurement for explosive force, then at least be sure you have the skill to back that mess up. This guy shouldn't call himself "Megaton". I've popped balloons that have more punch than his films.

reviewText: Films that don't need or can't realistically accommodate a sequel are hashed out all the time, and Taken is no exception. The film reinvented Liam Neeson as a late-in-life action hero (despite having a few successful action films earlier in his career) and was a surprise hit at the box office thanks to its neutered PG-13 rating. A harder cut surfaced on Blu-ray, and the famous monologue of Neeson threatening the kidnappers on the phone entered pop culture, giving the studio hope that a sequel would do big business. The gamble worked, and the sequel took more money than the first. Is it any good? I expected the worst, but I actually prefer this movie to the first.Made four years later, but set unspecified years later, Bryan Mills and infantile daughter Kim are still getting over their disastrous trip to Paris (where you are guaranteed to to be kidnapped and sold into sexual slavery, so don't even think about it). Former-bitch former-wife Lenore is now back in love with Bryan and surprises him on his last day of a Istanbul assignment by showing up at the hotel. New trip, new disaster. Will the Mills family ever learn to stay at home in America where nothing ever bad ever happened to anyone?The daddy of the evil kidnapper in the first movie has somehow managed to find Mills and has an army of lowlifes (all of them dressing in dirty 1980s clothes that seemed to have washed-up in a lost container on a Yugoslavian beach some time in 1991) willing to sacrifice their existence for the most arbitrary of reasons (untaxed pay and the boss' approval). Mills and wife are quickly kidnapped and it's up to Kim to rescue them and let him loose to kill, kill, kill the evil foreign men.I found this film to be more exciting and the danger was ramped-up. It lacks the variety of locations of the first movie (almost every scene is set in a dark alley), and there are some ludicrous plot contrivances (Mills' CIA pals fixing everything with a phonecall or the fact that Jean-Claude still has the same job despite his massive corruption being exposed) but it moves fast enough to make it a non-issue. The action is hard-hitting and Neeson is still a force to be reckoned with as he effortlessly dominates the movie with his presence.The Blu-ray looks great in 2.40:1 1080p. The movie was shot in a strange combination of Super35 and anamorphic Panavision with lots of high brightness and contrast. Not amazing photography, but it looks nice. The DTS HD-MA sound has some good punchy effects during the action scenes. A bunch of decent extras are included.

reviewerName: Jacques COULARDEAU "A soul doctor, so to say"
reviewText: This film is done for the European public first of all but it should work in the USA with the nostalgia of so many action films and of course Midnight Express. But the main difference with this film is that here we do not know why the Albanians and this American security agent are fighting. Albania was on the border of the war in Kosovo. So we know there is a political problem and stake. Albania was the communist country that had absolutely banned all religious activities and all religious expression. So, what's left to keep the Albanians away from kidnapping young girls and women to feed them in their lucrative prostitution network? Nothing, not even religious beliefs to try to repent, at least five minutes a day. And we just learned Albania is getting ready to join the European Community. Really? Yes, so they say in the media.Even more surprising is the fact that the action mainly takes place in Turkey, in Istanbul. Turkey wants to join the European Community and the Euro Zone and that's tricky to provide the European public with that totally violent, terroristic and immoral image of Istanbul. Is it trying to ask this question from all Europeans: Are you going to let that country enter the European Community as if they were peaceful and law-abiding? Or is it asking that other question from the Turks: How can you dare to want to enter the European Community when you are not even able to prevent your territory from being used like that by terrorists without any other motivation than their personal vengeance?The film is ambiguous and very obscure as for its political and ideological motivations. It cannot move the Americans who know nothing about these political questions, but it may frankly be disturbing to the European or Turkish public.But it is a film by Luc Besson. So there are other elements than just this unclear ideological context.First it is an action film and Luc Besson here uses an extremely rapid tempo with no slowing down except to increase the suspense and to make us fear the worst. The action is also extremely simple in the means it uses. No super technology. The good old simple cars and car chases, then a simple pager, then some simple guns: grenades, hand guns and some assault automatic guns. That's all. All the rest is simple running and tricky inventiveness. Of course the escape through the window and along a narrow cornice on the faade of a hotel has already been used but its simplicity works perfectly well.Second Luc Besson has to add a child, here a teenage daughter that should be just over sixteen, since she is trying to get her driver's license and she has already failed twice. Her being in any kind of danger is poignant of course, and her mother being captured and used as bait is just as bad. And Luc Besson cannot evade the cliché, but so well done and used, of the father fixation and of that father who saves his daughter first and his wife, at least twice. We remember Léon of course and the little girl he decides to help in her necessary vengeance since all her family has just been executed by some dumb terrorists. That's a syndrome if not a tic or even an idiosyncrasy of Luc Besson's: the father figure that saves the day of a daughter, a mother, a family, a victim of some terroristic gang violence. That gives a touch of empathy.The end then would not surprise at all and is so typical of Besson again. The daughter is over sixteen and so she is of age. So she has a boyfriend and the father is kind of jealous somewhere, but Besson must be aging since he is able to make the father step back from his protective jealousy concerning his daughter. Charming.Dr Jacques COULARDEAU

reviewText: Thanks to the first film of the TAKEN series, under the auspices of 20th Century Fox, Liam Neeson as butt-kicking ex-spy Bryan Mills has successfully rebranded himself as one of the elder statesman of action cinema, now able almost to be spoken in the same sentence as names like Willis or Stallone. Then after that came a series that should have pushed the point home that he didn't belong there, with films like THE A-TEAM and UNKNOWN, which were both terrifically bad films. Unfortunately, he reteamed with A-TEAM director Joe Carnahan for THE GREY, an existential survival thriller that was well-received amongst fans and not unliked by critics. So, the Neeson Express was still rolling, and Fox, never knowing when to let a good idea lie (see the ALIEN, PREDATOR or DIE HARD series for evidence of this), decided to try to create a franchise out of what could only really succeed as a one-off. This led us to TAKEN 2, and what is one of the most boring, most unentertaining and really, one of the stupidest films of the year.Basically, the film revolves around Mills' recently-divorced ex-wife Lenore (Famke Janssen, reprising her role) and daughter Kim (Maggie Grace, also reprising her ageless role) surprising him in Istanbul very shortly after he's concluded his protection service there. At the same time, the father (the wasted character actor Rade Serbedzija) of the "Good Luck" Albanian who Mills let fry in the chair from the first film, has sworn vengeance on Mills and his family. But instead of the daughter being taken, it's him and his wife. And Kim is the only one that can assist her father. And through a series of increasingly implausible scenarios, Mills takes the bad guys on to save his ex-wife.I know that some people felt that there could never be a sequel to a film like DIE HARD because of how singular that film felt. Four sequels later, they're still expanding the idea to a fault. Well, TAKEN, because of its specific plot (kidnapped daughter), can really only work once, and as evidenced by this film, it's true. Bryan Mills, while being a badass, is little else. His motivations to save the wife of his ex-wife, who seems very keen on rekindling their relationship after her latest marriage ends, seem much weaker than a father protecting his daughter, and his pursuit of their assailants seem much more languid and rote. This is obviously a film that is going to hold no surprises, and to be honest, that should be enough. But the direction by French-director-with-the-greatest-action-film-director-name-ever, Olivier Megaton (TRANSPORTER 3, COLOMBIANA) is, similarly to his previous work, pretty uninspired and has no real excitement or vitality to it. Even the "final fight sequence" is dull and unimpressive. Neeson is just going through the motions here. I appreciate that actors are working people, and that they need to get some change in their pockets, but Neeson must have turned down better films than this. Janssen just exists to look nearly unconscious through most of the film, and Grace, who I really loved on LOST, and thought she was a lot of fun in the film LOCKOUT, has an expanded role here, but still makes not much of an impression. Plus, how old is she supposed to be? In LOST, she seemed to be in her early to mid-twenties, but in these films, she seems to be in her teens, and it really doesn't work.I'm going to perhaps spoil something here, so you might want to not continue reading if you don't want to know more about the most idiotic point of the film. The film opens with Bryan looks to give his daughter driving lessons since she keeps flunking the parallel parking part. Of course, this means that a certain part of the film will require her to drive. When we get to this film's been-done-a-thousand-times-before car chase, she is inexplicably behind the wheel and instead of there being any beats where she is driving the car poorly, or is freaking out because she can't get the car in gear, she is driving this car like Jason Bourne on a bottle of No-Doz. She is doing things with a six-speed manual transmission that master stunt drivers would be envious of. And the finale of this chase scene culminates with Bryan instructing his daughter to drive DIRECTLY THROUGH the gates of the American Embassy without stopping, assuring that 50-caliber machine guns and other weapons begin firing at the car. And you know what? That's not even the stupidest part of the scene. It's when Bryan makes a call to one of his stateside spy buddies that puts an ignominous cap on this frighteningly moronic scene.If I didn't think that TAKEN 2 was a bad idea before I saw it, I can guarantee to you now that it's a way of wasting valuable time that you will never get back. Skip it.

reviewText: Recently watched movie review:*Taken 2 (2012)- 1/5Taken 2 is a sequel to the 2008 film (Taken) which is newly directed by Oliver Megaton. It stars Liam Neeson, Maggie Grace, Famke Janssen, and Rade Sherbedgia. I love the first movie, so does Taken 2 live up to my expectations? Ha, it's not even in the same league, and it's the worst movie I've seen so far this year.Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson) killed a lot of men while searching for his daughter, Kim (Maggie Grace), who was taken in Paris by a human trafficking ring. Family members of the men, whom he killed in the first film, are mourning those who died. Murad (Rade Sherbedgia) who's the employer of the men and father of Marko, a victim whom Bryan killed, swears revenge, and states that they will find Bryan to avenge the deaths of their loved ones. Murad and is men capture Bryan and his ex wife, Lenore (Famke Janssen), while Kim lucks out and helps her parents escape death.Taken 2 falls flat in every single way possible compared to the awesomeness of the first Taken movie. Let me start off by saying the only good thing about the film... (crickets), (crickets), (crickets)... That's right, there's nothing good to say about it.There are so many 'I just rolled my eyes' moments in the film, and there's very little that's believable; While Bryan is involved in a gun standoff with Mured's men, the kind men let him whip out his phone to warn Kim that he and Lenore are being taken (I just rolled my eyes). Kim can't pass 2 driving tests, but she can throw grenades, do geometry, jump from rooftop to rooftop, and can drive like a stunt driver in a chase scene (I just rolled my eyes). Murad, who knows Bryan can kill just about anyone, gives Lenore a baby gash, hangs her upside down, tells Bryan, who's tied to a pole, that she's got 30 minutes until she dies, leaves the room with them unattended, and expects everything to go as plan (I just rolled my eyes). When Bryan obviously breaks free and saves Lenore, he later fights some of Murad's men, but somehow he's got special powers this time around; Bryan can simply put his hands on someone's face, and that person will instantly die (I just rolled  myeyes).The first Taken was far more energetic, there was more dialog, the villain isn't old and pathetic, and events were much more believable. Taken 2 is soulless compared to the first, and should be avoided at all costs as this is a simple cash grab. If you're a fan of the first (like me) and wanted a sequel, use your imagination instead, and continue to just watch the first Taken. If you couldn't tell by now, Taken 2 gets a recommended 'must-pass.'

reviewText: "Taken 2" is half just a fun action movie (if this is your idea of fun) and half an attempt at understanding CIA Nietzschean Superman -one dude anti kidnapping-killing machine Bryan Mills.  Keep in mind that in the first Taken--which possessed an eerie mood that made it stand out, along with Liam Neeson's sinister bravado--Bryan Mills rescued his daughter from Albanian kidnappers in less than 72 hours and singlehandedly dismantled the Albanian mob in about half an hour.Not entirely so, it would seem.  In a slightly absurd plot device, Mills' daughter Kim (Maggie Grace, who is 30 and continues to play adolescents convincingly) and wife Lenore (Famke Jannsen) follow him to Istanbul, overwhelmed by enthusiasm because Kim has just learned to drive.Well, as you might guess, they are "Taken".  An Albanian mob boss is determined to avenge the deaths of his young sons whom Mills killed in an attempt to get his daughter back.  Though his sons were scum, the mob boss does sort of seem sympathetic at times, chaining up Mills and confronting him with his own, well, misdeeds.  "You connected my son Markos to an electrical current until his heart burst.  You killed these men like they were so many nothings."  Mills knows why he did what he did, but you get the impression he's a bit more mellow by the end of the film.  Well, after about 300 deaths and car wrecks that Evil Kanevel would not have the remote chance of surviving.  This isn't up to the par of the original film, but if you noticed Bryan Mills, you'll want to see it anyway.
summary: Fun and a bit of a character story

reviewText: By Jim Clark, publisher, Lee County Courier, Tupelo, MississippiYou may need to watch Taken again before embarking on Taken 2, since the stories are related.Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson), a retired intelligence agent, is having relationship problems with his wife, Lenore (Famke Janssen) because of his troublesome career. His daughter, Kim (Maggie Grace) loves him but can't stand his scrutiny of her boyfriends.Murad, the father of Marko, who Bryan electrocuted in the first Taken, has sworn to avenge the death. He plans to kill all three of the Mills.The family is supposed to go out together in Istanbul. Kim says she wants to stay by the pool, in a veiled attempt to give her father and mother some alone time.Bryan notices the couple are being followed, so instructs his wife to get out. She gets captured forcing Bryan to surrender, but not before calling Kim and warning her.He wakes up strapped to a pole, but able to contact Kim with a phone he's concealed. He wants her to go to the U.S. Embassy but Kim convinces her father that she can help. He instructs her to go back into the hotel and retrieve his suitcase, which is filled with grenades, guns and the like.I'll admit that Taken 2 leaves reality on the shelf after this point, but for action/adventure junkies it's still a must-see.Never mind that Rotten Tomatoes gave it a 21% rating.It grossed $139,548,476 in North America, and $232,044,000 Internationally, meaning a total of $371,592,476. I suspect the DVD release will just add to that bankroll.
summary: Common folks love it, critics not so much

reviewText: This is a good movie but not as well done as the first Taken film. There was still a lot of action and it had a fasted paced plot and storyline but the concept was just not as fresh. In some of the areas the scenarios were just a little hard to believe.Byran Mills (Liam Neeson) is in the protection business using his skills that he learned in the CIA to protect wealthy people for a lot of money. His family life is a wreck as he is divorced and his daughter lives with her mom. After rescuing his daughter in the first Taken film he becomes a target of international terrorists who seek revenge for the deaths of their family members (Sons) at the hands of Bryan who killed them as he rescued his kidnapped daughter.As Bryan's ex-wife and daughter meet up with him in Istanbul the terrorists gather to enact plans to kidnap them all and have the added joy of torturing his family in front of him...Liam Neeson does his regular spectacular best in this movie playing the highly skilled ex-CIA agent on a mission to save his family. There are many good chase scenes, gun battles and fights to entertain any action movie junkie. I really enjoyed them. The only down side for me is that Bryan puts his daughter at risk and despite the fact that he had a communication device neither he or his daughter sought out help from the CIA or the US Embassy to rescue them.My wife and I still liked the movie and we rated it 4 stars as a good action movie. The acting and the action in the film are first class and if you like that kind of movie then you will enjoy this one.

reviewText: look no further than Liam Neeson.  With Taken (which I have not seen) and Taken 2 (which I have), Neeson proves he has the intelligence, resourcefulness, cool composure, and presence to sell us on a new Bond.If the first Taken (as I understand it) was an efficiently violent revenge fantasy, Taken 2 is basically an efficiently violent "revenge for the revenge fantasy" of the first movie.  I will not regurgitate the plot here.  I refer you to Steven Aldersley's Taken 2 review for that.  Instead, I wish to pursue the strong Bondian elements that propel this fast, exciting flick, particularly Neeson's character's  (Bryan's) cool intelligence.  Bryan is captured and hooded , along with his ex-wife Lenore (Famke Janssen) by vengeful Albanian father Rade (Murad Hoxha) grieving for the white slavery mastermind son that Bryan killed in the first movie for attempting to kidnap his daughter Kim (Maggie Grace).  However, he is able to compose a mental map of his surroundings (Istanbul, Turkey) by listening to distinct sounds and calculating the intervals between them.  That way, he is able to convey a meticulous sequence of directions to Kim, who managed to stay safe at the hotel, so she can pinpoint his approximate location and provide him with a handgun to help him free himself and possibly Lenore.  I don't know if this is plausible, but it certainly seems ingenious.Even before all the action begins, we appreciate the precautions and weapons Bryan takes and accumulates (including mini-cell phones and other devices) to handle any dangerous exigency.  Later in the movie, even after being beaten and chained in a filthy basement, it's gratifying to see Bryan not only attempt to free himself, but also give those precise instructions to Lenore, and particularly Kim, to help him and them escape their predicament.  Realistically, both Lenore and Kim are fearful and uncertain what to do, but Bryan's cool CIA-operative professionalism helps keep them focused.  He may be retired, but Bryan is such a one-man assault gang, you get the feeling that Rade and his gang, despite their savage ruthlessness, never really stood a chance.Yes, Taken 2 is quite an enjoyable action thrill ride, but I am rating it about 3.5 stars for the following reasons: 1) as other posters have mentioned, much of the action, especially the taxi chase through the very narrow Istanbul street, was shot in that nauseating shaky-cam style that made it hard to follow the action sometimes, and made you wonder how Bryan, for all his skill, actually made it through alive.  I thought Kim was gonna collide with some car any minute - and her without a driver's license, 2) there's a slight whiff of xenophobia, especially in the depiction of Istanbul.  From a distance, it is a magnificent metropolis, but once the movie gets closer, you notice the extreme poverty and claustrophobia of the favela-like neighborhoods.  It looks forbidding.  The Turkish Tourist Board, probably just recovering from "Midnight Express"'s unflattering portrayal, now has to contend with this movie's, and later, ironically, the latest Bond flick Skyfall's depiction.  First the Albanians, now the Turks.  Europe doesnt seem like such a nice place. 3) you have what Roger Ebert calls the Fallacy of the Talking Killer, which states that instead of killing the hero outright, the villain wastes time boasting and talking about what terrible things he'll do to him, giving the hero a chance to retaliate.  If Rade despises Bryan so much for killing his son, why toy with him so long?  Yeah, yeah, you wouldn't have a movie.  So you go with it.Oh, whatever.  Taken 2 is nevertheless an efficient, sharp, involving movie with not only action, but also snatches of humor (e.g. Bryan's reaction to Kim's latest boyfriend, the taxi's barreling towards the U.S. Embassy - "The soldiers will get out of the way.") So what can we expect of Taken 3? Hmm, I know.  Kim and her new boyfriend Jamie (Luke Grimes) go to Bratislava and encounter a "Hostel" situation.  Bryan to the rescue!One more trivial thought.  My friend Ron Spiegel, who watched the movie with me, thought Rade looked like "the most interesting man in the world" from the Dos Equus commercials. Stay thirsty (for revenge) my friends!
summary: If Daniel Craig Ever Gets Tired of the Bond Gig...

reviewText: I have no complaints about Taken 2. It was far better than I thought it would be. It was just as action packed as the first movie, and I believe for a sequel the story was just as good. I will be the first to tell you that a sequel is not going to be better than the first, but this has got to be one of the best sequels of the last 10 years or so. I can honestly tell you that I would put it evenly with Taken 1. This is probably because at the beginning of the movie they made sure to make it have as much character development as the first movie. It really felt like they wanted to truly continue the story of what would happen to a family after the events of the first movie had taken place, and they even brought back the entire supporting cast from the first. They didn't just try to put more explosives and more action and less character development which is the mold that 99% of sequels seem to take. If you enjoyed Taken then I don't believe there is anyway that you won't enjoy Taken 2.
summary: Liam Neeson is back doing what he does best.

reviewText: One of the things I most like about Amazon is this freedom to write reviews. Disagreeing with previous reviewers is sometimes a key factor in that enjoyment. Unlike many before me, I LOVE "Taken 2" with Liam Neeson and found it superior to its predecessor, "Taken."My 13-year-old great-nephew also loved the movie--so mark two for "Taken 2" for its multi-generational approvals. There's a slow beginning--too slow for my nephew until the action begins, then pow! the rest of the movie. Nonstop action! After the movie, my nephew said the slow beginning was necessary to set up the story that follows. Although he is a sophisticated movie buff, almost anyone would get it that the slow beginning is necessary.This time out, Neeson's daughter is car driving age--there's a big deal about not passing her driving test--a fact that becomes null and void by movie's end. In "Taken" Neeson kills the son of an Albanian mobster. Some kind of blood feud goes on in Albania much like the American Hatfield-McCoy feud. Neeson spilled Albanian blood, now the Albanian mob must spill Neeson and family blood.The goons kidnap Neeson and his wife, the daughter escapes. One of the most unusual chase scenes in movie history takes place on the colorful rooftops of ancient buildings in Istanbul, Turkey. It is wild!In the first "Taken" the daughter is kidnapped and sold as a sex slave. In this movie she becomes the hero. Movie history is changing. She also is part of a thrilling car chase, providing her with a set of certain skills in driving.The movie is worth watching just to hear Neeson say he has a set of certain skills he will use after he escapes his own imprisonment. "I will find you" is his omninous, now iconic statement much like Eastwood and Schwarzennegger use.
summary: More thrilling than the first Taken

reviewText: I very much enjoyed this movie.  Maybe Taken 1 was a little better but Taken 2 was still great! (And, I will buy the DVD when it comes out.)  There is just something real special about watching Liam Neeson go after these brutal, murdering creeps.This time the film begins in Albania, where the bodies are being unloaded from the airplane -- the bodies of the bad guys that Neeson killed in Taken 1.  As they are being buried, the grieving family surrounding the dead, the head guy and father of one or more of them, vows revenge against Neeson. (I mean, forget the fact that THEY started the whole thing by stealing his daughter.)The scene shifts to Los Angeles, California, where Neeson's former wife is in the midst of a divorce from her second husband and the daughter is dating.  Neeson is leaving for a couple of days of work in Instanbul and invites them to join him when the job is finished.  As you probably guessed, all the excitement begins on foreign soil, as the bad guys go after Neeson and his family.It is a great movie, with lots of action.  Yes, some things seem a bit of a stretch, but then (like I always say) the movie you really want to see is the one where a super hero beats all the odds and does incredible things.Will these bad guys EVER LEARN?

reviewText: The first Taken really catapulted Liam Neeson in an unexpected genre: the action super hero. It was fresh, original and exciting. That was in large part to Neeson himself, who is so unassuming as ex-CIA Agent Bryan Mills; but he is such a talented Actor and the characterization was done so well without doing too much in the first film. So when Taken 2 came out, I was really excited. However, with the good, there is the bad.*Spoilers ahead*GOOD: Neeson is as awesome as ever. More importantly, he continues to be believable and virtually carries the whole film with some help of Maggie Grace, aka, Kim Mills. The whole cast was back, from the ex-wife to his group of spy friends to the French Inspector, even if briefly for most. The plot had lots of potential with the Albanian family of the men Mills killed, coming after the Mills family for revenge. The action is good, fast-pace and typical Luc Besson, ala Transporter.BAD: Pretty much everything else. I don't mind repetition when done right. However, the screenplay, as a whole, is a complete bust and tries waaaaay to hard to recapture the energy and quiet intelligence of the first Taken. For one, it nearly mimics the first movie in every respect, including dialogue, which got cringeworthy. It is also set just months after Kim's rescue, which didn't make any sense since the actress was 29 at the time and didn't look like a high school girl about to get her driver's license. The characterization of the ex-wife, Lenore, is the second  worst in the movie, but Famke Janssen did her best but it wasn't good enough to compete with Neeson or even Grace. The overall performance is forced, stilted and cliched. The worst characterization of the story is Murad, the Albanian leader who kidnaps the MIlls and is the father of one of the slain kidnappers who first kidnapped Kim. The writers did poorly in developing a truly evil counterpart to Mills. He is not this scary evil villain that you're glad the good guy disposes of accordingly. He was not even close to Mills stature and to not have a villain who is worthy and equal to Mills was just pathetic and for me, weakens the movie.Ugh, the dialogue; it got distracting and was horrendous. Ignore it to truly enjoy the movie. Besson (The Professional,La Femme Nikita), who is one of my favorite directors, is not the best writer; he should have stuck to directing this film himself which is something he does best and this movie could have used it. The cast does its best with what it was given but even they seemed to know how bad it was throughout the film. Again, the overall CONCEPT of the plot held promise but it quickly unraveled to the predictable and nonsensical. Thankfully, the action is what propels the film, as well as Neeson's electric performance.
summary: Watch it for the action and Neeson's cool moves--but nothing else.

reviewText: Taken 2 is nowhere near as good as Taken. While Taken isn't the most inventive action film, it was very enjoyable and had some genuine excitement. This is not the case for Taken 2. Taken 2 takes the "Bourne" approach even more than the first, utilizing the very cliched shaky cam and quick cuts. Quick cuts are even used in slow dialogue scenes, and for no obvious reason. As an editor myself, I believe cuts should be precise, intentional, and purposeful. As I was studying some of the shots in this film, I came to the conclusion that the editors didn't really put much thought into WHY the cuts were being made, other than to make the film faster-paced, and it didn't work. Also, the director overused high-shutter speed cameras to "intensify" fight scenes. This made me dislike the film even more, as this is an extremely overused technique. This film wasn't just bad technically. The writing was poor. A friend I was with even pointed out some contradictions in the dialogue, causing some serious continuity issues. The writers were very sloppy and it is clear the focus of this film was not on the story or the writing, but the action, which is something a film should NEVER do.I apologize for not being able to find anything good with this film. Taken 2 is a prime example of what I dislike about action films: fast cuts, shaky cam, and high shutter speeds, not to mention, poor writing and dry acting. This film was obviously action-based with weak characters and a very flimsy script. I would recommend this to anyone who wants to go to the movies and literally be in a coma and not use their brain whatsoever. This is easily a candidate for the worst film of the year.
summary: One of the worst movies I've ever seen.

reviewText: "Taken 2" is great! This is how the story goes: Bryan Mills is the retired CIA agent with a "particular set of skills" who stopped at nothing to save his daughter Kim from kidnappers. When the father of one of the villains Bryan killed swears revenge, and takes Bryan and his wife hostage in Istanbul, Bryan enlists Kim to help them escape. Bryan then employs his unique tactics to get his family to safety and systematically take out the kidnappers, one by one.The cast led by Liam Neeson (as Bryan), Maggie Grace (as Kim) & Famke Janssen (as Lenore) is great. The directing by Olivier Megaton is great. The screenplay by Luc Besson (who also produced) & Robert Mark Kamen is great.The music by Nathaniel Mechaly is great. The cinematography by Romain Lacourbas is great. The film editing by Camille Delamarre & Vincent Tabaillon is great. The production design by Sebastien Inizan is great. The art direction by Nanci Roberts & Atilla Yilmaz is great. The set dressings by Joshua Foster, John Markovich & Franck 'Frenchy' Brousse is great. The special effects coordinated by Donn Markel & supervised by Philippe Hubin is great. The stunts coordinated by Mark Vanselow, Alain Figlarz, Laurent Demianoff & Michel Julienne is great.This is a great action sequel to a great action movie that is entertaining and fast-paced. Liam Neeson is still as great as ever in his return as Bryan Mills. This is just as great as the first "Taken". This is one of the best movies of the fall season.

reviewText: Another intense installment of the Mills' family misfortunes.Criticisms that the team behind 'Taken', including one of my favorite director/producers Luc Besson, are repeating themselves is fair.However, and this is important, that's like criticizing a home run because the batter only just made it over the wall.The fact that the ball went over at all is a blessed near-miracle nowadays and we should be grateful; especially in the US market where facile, plastic, and pathetic are commonplace. In all honesty, I haven't seen such a dearth of weak sorry excuses for filmmaking since the late 70s-thru-mid 80s, where schlock was king. This is a new Dark Age for many cinephiles. The digital revolution allowing ill-trained, ill-equipped, lowest common denominators access to the technical and commercial inroads that were previously closed off, disgorging a stunning plethora of cinematic garbage.So remember that when considering formula films. What they lack in creativity, they more than make up for in pure adrenaline enjoyment.As before, retired field agent Bryan Mills is placed in the position of having to defend his family from a host of nogoodniks. However, in a twist, he finds himself as the primary target.Having righteously killed his daughter's kidnappers, and as family is the theme of the franchise, what he had forgotten was that those worthless turds had family too. Angry families. Gangster families.Despite the fact that Marco, a.k.a. Mr. "Good Luck", was a sincere bleeping scumbag who kidnapped young women, violently raped and abused them, then dumped them into slave pits to suffer a horrific and sickening life of drug induced prostitution and an anonymous garbage dump of a grave - his father doesn't care what his p.o.s. of a son did, only that it was his son that was killed. And he wants his pound of flesh. Literally.The obvious failing, and one that did slightly annoy, was the plot avoidance of Revenge Rule No. 1: You can never go back.Once you burn a bridge, especially when it's filled with people, that's gone forever. You can never return to where that bridge once stood. But what do the Mills do? Seriously, Europe should've been dead to them. Even an English or Irish trip would've been risky. The continent? Forget it. There are at least three other global land masses one can explore over one's lifetime. Lotta room in the world not to have to repeatedly bump into people. Especially people who detest and hate you.Other than that minor complaint, 'Two' was a kickass epinephrine rush!Very solid four.Personal Note:- I'm a huge fan of Leland Orser and would love to see a film just about his character. The man shares the technical, political and badass intelligence background as the main character, Bryan Mills, but seems infinitely more hooked into the system. Two pennies: His backstory has a ton of potential.

reviewText: When I first heard about this movie, I wondered what kind of storyline would be presented here - the daughter being kidnapped again, perhaps? Instead, the tables are turned as her parents are kidnapped and she has to go and rescue them. This was a pleasing turnabout that made the story refreshing.I was blown away by the sheer arrogance of the kidnappers. The head of the kidnappers refuses to think about the wrong that his dead relatives committed (participating in human trafficking/the sex slave trade) and acts as if they are martyrs and wants revenge against the man who killed them while searching for and rescuing his kidnapped daughter. The old man had no care for the lives of the girls that were ruined as a result of the trafficking and his relatives' part in this. I doubt the stupid old man would like it if his own daughters/granddaughters were victims of the sex slave trade, hm? But that made him real as a villain, that he thought he was the only right one and that his relatives did not deserve to die, no matter what horrible wrongs they did. Overall a good movie, even if it's not quite as good as the first.

reviewText: This sequel to "Taken" is more of the same, the first film was so believable & was a real no holds barred suspense thriller about a former CIA operative who knows his way around the world & gets the guys who take his daughter for the purpose of white slavery, he kills many of them in his quest to find her, & rescues her at the end, this follow-up had a good premise, with some family members of the people he killed in the first film wanting revenge, but I feel they really should have had the bad guys coming to Los Angeles to get their revenge rather than have another overseas mishap, some years have passed since the first film's events, & Liam Neeson once again commands the screen as a over protective father, there are some highlights such as him & his ex-wife(Famke Jansen) sort of re-connecting, but then he has a overseas assignment where he is protecting a world leader, once the job is done his ex-wife & daughter make a surprise appearance, this is where you really have to suspend belief, why would a daughter who was kidnapped want to take another overseas trip?, why would her mother want to even take her overseas after what happened in the first film, & why would Neeson even be happy they were there?...knowing the dangers all around them, what follows is more of the same as Neeson & Jansen are taken this time, & the daughter (Maggie Grace) has to help her parents, again there is so much suspension of disbelief here, when what they should have done is have the bad guys come to L.A. & Neeson fight them there, that would have been more believable, this like many sequels suffers from sheer laziness on the part of the filmakers who know they have an audience & do nothing different, this one has its share of action, but it could have been sooo much better!!...& it wasn't.....this one is a mixed bag for me.

reviewText: Unfortunately this sequel to the excellent "Taken" (2008) provides little new and is certainly inferior to the original.  In this Olivier Megaton directed money grab, Liam Neeson remains effective as a former government secret agent.  In the original, he goes after Albanian goons involved in the sex trade.  They made the mistake of kidnapping Bryan Mill's (Neeson) teen age daughter Kim (Maggie Grace) which put Bryan in full on battle mode where he is able to use "his special skills."  This time, Kim's is still a teenager trying to pass her driver's license exam after a couple failures.As an aside, I'm a big fan of the TV show "Californication" and 29 year old Maggie Grace has her own "special skills" in her role as a rock `n roll groupie in the recent season.  For her next role maybe she can play a high school student on "Glee."  Anyway, even if Kim can't parallel park, she can sure drive the hell out of a Mercedes cab, complete with a manual transmission.  Hard to focus on the plot, or lack thereof.Bryan is on assignment in Turkey and the Albanian head of the family, Murad Krasniqi (reliable Rade Serbedzija), is out for revenge.  He and his henchman travel to Istanbul and get a bonus in that Kim and Bryan's ex-wife Lenore (Famke Janssen) meet him there.  This time Lenore and Bryan are kidnapped and Kim must play a key role in getting them rescued.  There's nothing overly offensive except the script, especially some of the dialog.  Like "Kim, drive faster" or "Kim, go go go" and of course Kim freaking out.  There was no need to make this more-of-the-same movie except for box office receipts of course.

reviewText: You won't find any film schools showing this flick, but you will find lots of regular people enjoying it when they sit down to watch.  Liam Neeson is in typical Liam form (at least post-Schindler form), the villains are ugly thugs, and the women are both (no, wait...there is a 3rd woman...she appears twice for a total of about 24 seconds) attractive.  There is plenty of action, and a super-simple story line that drives this 90+ minute film along with nary a wasted camera shot.This movie is a lot of fun, but it is absolutely ridiculous.  I laughed as I left the theater because of how bad some of the movie is:1) Liam Neeson's hand-to-hand fighting skills must have atrophied a lot, because every time he is in a fight with a thug (did I mention they were all ugly?) the director uses about 6 camera angles to film the fight, and uses editing so choppy that you can't tell what anyone involved in the fight is doing.2) Maggie Grace is playing the high-school aged daughter of Liam!  She looks like she's about 30 here, and her bad hair-dye is matched only by her too-brief nude scene (back only, no butt).3) SPOILER HERE:  The mom is like a character out of the old Monty Python sketch..she is 'not quite dead' about five times in the flick. And every time she's 'not quite dead' all Liam has to do to make her better is pat her back.  It's so funny, that the audience was cracking up the 3rd time it happened.Overall, this was a fun night at the movies.  I loved how cheesy the movie was, and had a great time.
summary: Dumb Fun: Ridiculous Movie Provides Lots of Entertainment
