reviewText: In which obsessively compulsive CIA veteran Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson) and his estranged family are abducted by a village of Albanian Muslims hell-bent on avenging the other half of the village, whom Mills single-handedly slaughtered in Taken 1. I hadn't had the pleasure of that particular piece of cinema as I took my seat in the Odeon Leicester Square: it turned out not to matter.We open with a glamorous helicopter shot of an unglamorous Albanian truck, bouncing up a dirt road to a communal hilltop burial ground where, clutching a fistful of dust over his family's manifold fallen, patriarchal villain Murad (Rade Serbedzija) gravely swears vengeance on Mills' head, beseeching most of what remains of his extended family (still handsomely stocked with uncles, second cousins and nephews) to join him.That Mills only came to be involved after the village kidnapped his daughter Kim (Maggie Grace) and sold her (among others) into slavery does not upset the Albanians' moral calculus. Burial ceremonies complete, they mount a convoy of dusty Mercs and make haste to Istanbul where, as luck would have it, Bryan is attempting a low-key reconciliation with his wife Lenore (Famke Janssen) and daughter (yes: the same one who was kidnapped last time she left L.A: clearly not the lesson-learning type).Mills' patiently-recounted OCD, which sees him insist on (ahem) polishing his own bonnet at the car wash, seems not to extend to keeping his dependents reasonably out of harm's way: After a scene-setting educational ride across the Bosphorus ("it's where East meets West" etc etc) and the obligatory aerial shot of Istanbul's grand mosque as the muezzin calls the faithful to prayer, the Albanian Mercs roll in. Cue mayhem.This is big, dumb fun on a Luc Besson scale. As long as you can balance between being neither taking it at all seriously nor finding it entirely absurd (a challenge with which most of the audience, including your correspondent, struggled) it will keep you entertained.Joyously-named director Olivier Megaton - vraiment de l'ecole Besson - certainly gives it the by name/by nature treatment: many bottomless semi-automatic magazines, carelessly-tossed hand grenades, twisted necks, caved-in skulls, improvised shivs, exploding cars and kick boxing demonstrations are required to progress a surprisingly tedious plot to a very pre-ordained conclusion. Megaton doesn't even bother with a they-think-its-all-over-but-he's-not-yet-dead final scene bad-guy reprise. Instead, proceedings draw to a indecently hasty conclusion, the film ending with a bookend glamorous helicopter shot of - wait for it - the family eating waffles in a pier-end restaurant in Venice Beach. This about says it all.Why Liam Neeson, a sound actor and surely the sine qua non of the picture, felt at all compelled to make it is a mystery. There is little craft in it, and and the dialogue only works as irony.Strictly routine.Olly Buxton
summary: Megatons of excitement in this contractual obligations affair

reviewText: This is the review. You have to focus. Don't let your eyes leave this page. The words on this webpage have the following meaning. Parallel parking's difficulty level is now far greater than the difficulty level of evading multiple Turkish police interceptors in the maze of streets in the centre of Istanbul (not Constantinople).You have to pull yourself together now, and finish reading this review. As long as your father is there in the passenger seat commanding you in short, staccato word-bursts, you can drive a Mercedes 5-speed taxicab through narrow twisting alleys and never miss a gear. Keep going.I'll bet you never knew the U.S. Embassy in Istanbul was located at the centre of a maze of twisting streets and narrow alleys. It's turns out that's where the U.S. likes to locate its embassies, at least in majority-Islamic countries: far from the airport, in the midst of the city where there are the tightest, narrowest streets, where you can't see what's up ahead of the motorcade too well, and with lots of irregular architecture on either side; lots of good routes for escorting those important diplomats to and from the airport.You know, "Taken 2" had my interest, as did the much better first in the "Taken" franchise. But then it got silly. And I started to laugh a lot more than I should've. "Taken 3" should be the story of Kim (Maggie Grace) dating this young Albanian-American guy whose family aren't killers, slavers, or kidnappers (they own a shop that sells designer clothes); that'll be good for some dramatic tension between the boyfriend and the Bryan Mills character. And then Kim and her boyfriend get taken by some vengeance-minded Americans who've decided they've had enough with Albanians kidnapping people all over the world. And then Bryan and Lenore Mills get taken by a group of Albanians who mistake them for the previously mentioned Americans who kidnapped Kim and her boyfriend, whom the Albanians are trying to rescue. And then THOSE Albanians get kidnapped by a group of Chuvash villagers from north of the Volga River. The Chuvash villagers then hire a highly trained group of Faroe Islands natives whose specialty is abduction, to kidnap themSELVES, and the entire story is told backwards, with all the scenes in reverse order. Christopher Nolan will direct."Taken 2" is good for what it's supposed to be: a movie with a lot of action. Car action. Gun action. Hand-to-hand combat action.  It's just hard to take any of it seriously. The first one had the advantage of that premise that clearly sells a lot of movies: (deep voice) they %#*!ed with the wrong man. Also, moviegoers seem to take a degree of perverse pleasure in seeing innocence get threatened, as long as those doing the threatening of innocence are horrifyingly punished and killed later on in the film. "Taken 2" it's like... nobody cares if Mr. and Mrs. Mills get kidnapped. They're not innocent, playful ingénues with hearts of gold, facing an horrific fate that would make the strongest person blanch with terror.But hey, the performers need to take a bow, because they never falter in their honest portrayals of these made-up characters. Their conviction is perfect, even when things get silly. In "Taken 1" Maggie Grace had to create a convincing, true to life persona out of the rawest human emotions (extreme excitement/happiness and extreme terror) and succeeded admirably. In "Taken 2" she plays the cliché part of "18 year-old girl in love for the first time" like a real, live person and Not a cliché; matured by her ordeals, but still a bit of a romantic and starlet-wannabe. She turns in a better, more varied performance here than she did as the San Fernando Valley cliché in "Taken 1."And can anyone think of anything bad to say about Famke Janssen or Rade Serbedzija? If so, those people had best not come near me, for I have several choice words I would fain share with such people.And no matter how bad a movie gets, I will not, I will Never diss Admiral Zeus from Planet Krull. The man is a genius. I wish I had even a fraction of this man's genius. Watch the very last scene of "Taken 2" for a bit of this man's infective genius. Thanks, Liam. Now I'm unable to greet friends of that name without almost laughing.

reviewText: Taken II suffers from the same problem 'Taken I' did. It's big on well choreographed action sequences, has good acting by Liam Neeson, nice locations, fairly good production qualities, directing, etc. But it lacks any common sense at all. Most action films where there are a lot of bullet's flying and car crashes require the viewer to suspend belief to a certain level. But these two films take excessive license with it, and often to laughable levels. I pretty much hated the first one. Though I found it very entertaining on a brainless sort of level with great action sequences, I simply could not get past the rediculous notion that a girl who's father worries something will happen to her get's kidnapped the second she shows up in Paris. She's literally targeted the very moment she lands. That sort of license pushes the envelope so far that it's insulting to the audience's common sense. That particular part of the script and the plot was pathetic and just plain stupid. Also the girl who played his daughter was very plastic and cheesy. I saw Taken II last night and did find it entertaining, and I liked it a little more than I liked the first one, but only because I already realized you have to leave all your brains at the door in order to enjoy it at all. In the first one she's just plastic and annoying. In this one she's not only plastic and annoying, but she's running around on rooftops throwing hand granades all over Istanbul, and driving getaway cars like a pro stunt driver when earlier on in the movie she's studying for her drivers license and can't even figure out how to park right. This one takes more license with the stupidity than the first one for sure. This is sort of like watching a John Woo or Michael Bay movie with slightly better production values. What I mean by that is that Woo and Bay action films usually cross the line into the rediculous and are generally rather out there. But thta is not to say Woo's earlier asian films were bad, they were really ok for what they were. But movies like Armageddon & The Rock for example are generally liked by a lot of people but are also hated by a lot of people. And if you hated those movies then you likely know where I am comming from. This is typical of the formula you expect from a Steven Seagal movie. Lots of action but short on brains. Also when I saw the first Taken I kept imagining Keifer Sutherland playing the main character. To all intents and purposes the Neeson character is a carbon copy of Jack Bauer, still I loved Neeson as this character. In fact without him the film would not be memorable for most people who like it now. The Taken movies play like cheesebal B style action movies, but still on a brainless action level both movies are pretty entertaining. So I hated and liked both movies, hence the 2 star rating.
summary: Entertaining as long as you leave all your common sense somewhere else

reviewText: Liam Neeson reprises his role as the lethal, always alert agent Bryan Mills, in Taken 2, and I'm very happy he's back, this being a welcome action role return for Neeson.The story follows the logical revenge plot of the villains' surviving Father, of who's sons Bryan took down in his determined venture to save his daughter from a network of slavers. This round, Bryan Mills enters Istanbul and his ex wife and daughter visit him just as the enemy is closing in.FAST CAMERA CUTS: 24 cuts every 10 seconds?Most of the action scenes of which there are plenty (car chase, foot chase, gun battles, hand to hand combat) directed by Oliver Megaton is up for debate. For example, when action begins, there seems to be a sequence of 20 film shots for every five seconds of film, resulting in an MTV like barrage of imagery. This can work if done right, but here, the action, although frantic and full of energy, becomes harder to follow for some viewers, myself included. Just think of the stealth take downs of Batman Begins to picture the style of elbow shots and hard to follow close ups, rendering the battle a series of hard to track motions that don't add up to a cohesive fight all the time.It comes down to the cinematography, director and editor to make sure the audience can easily follow the action, but here, it's a flash of close ups of steering wheel horns, motion blurred elbows with the occasionally well done distance shots so we understand where the character is in relation to the environment and enemy, Thankfully, the firearm battles are done better, the car chase is overall exciting, and the final fist fight, against a very tough and formidable enemy, results in a well done hand to hand battle (though the editing still leaves a question mark at it's conclusion). The final fight works, because the majority of camera shots show the full body of both fighters, avoiding the extreme close ups of an earlier battle. Why do I mention all of this? Because Taken 1 delivered consistently easy to follow, really well done action scenes.In the end, Taken 2 is an enjoyable follow up to Taken, and recommended for anyone who enjoyed the ever alert and ready to kick butt style of Neeson's Bryan Mills character.Taken 2 ends up being a decent action movie. If they make Taken 3, bring back the editor and team from Part 1.ACTION: 6/10. Plenty of energetic action, though the cinematography/editing is sometimes hard to follow, it flicks through film shots like a flip book. Not a good approach for action movies.STORY: 8/10. Logical revenge plot and a well done story.ACTING: 8/10. No complaints here.OVERALL: 7/10.
summary: TAKEN 2: Excessive, fast Camera Cuts nearly ruin the action

reviewText: Being a huge fan of the first Taken, I was extremely skeptical of how the sequel would turn out. Knowing how Hollywood works, if there is a formula that works, Hollywood would take the liberty and try to milk the cow until it completely dries up. The original Taken (although not a  perfect film) was a great action thriller that had a simple premise but also had characters that were entertaining to watch thanks to the leading role of Liam Neeson.  The first film was about one man practically going against an entire army, going through whatever it takes to save his kidnapped daughter. Yes it was a very simple plot, but personally I found the execution to be thoroughly entertaining to watch.  The action was stellar, the scenarios were well thought out and most importantly you were watching the movie to the very end to make sure Liam Neeson's character does save his daughter.4 years later comes the release of Taken 2, the direct sequel. One thing I did appreciate about Taken 2 was the fact that the story didn't pull off a "Hangover 2" and just recreate the same movie in a different location. The plot, although familiar, was actually well thought out, and I believe that whomever took the time to write Taken 2 really thought of the best possible way to connect this film and the first Taken.  HOWEVER, what went wrong was simply the way the film was executed. The execution was very poor to say the very least and the director of this film should be ashamed of himself. Just about everything that made the first Taken so great, has suffered immensely in this second film. The only thing that saves this film from being absolute trash was the presence of Liam Neeson, but even he wasn't in top form. The acting from everybody including the great Liam Neeson felt incredibly flat; I just didn't feel the same sense of urgency as I did watching the first film which is awful because this movie is labeled as a thriller. The action sequences were horrid as well; I was glad I didn't catch this in the theaters because I am 100% sure that all the shaky fight scenes would have given me a headache. None of the villains in this movie were memorable whatsoever, I couldn't tell one guy from the other with the exception of the father of the sons Liam Neeson killed in the first movie, but I just didn't find him menacing, just annoying.As I am a fan of the first film, I found that Taken 2 was without a doubt an unnecessary movie that should not have been released. There were few instances where I found that the film succeeded as far as the plot, mainly in the middle of the film where Liam Neeson was instructing his daughter on how to find the location of him and her mother, but ultimately those scenes could not justify an entire 90 minutes of film. The film felt rushed and the acting was not done well at all; maybe if it was directed by a different person the film would've turned out decent but sadly this is what we have to settle with.

reviewText: The last time we saw Kim Mills, daughter/ victim in the first "Taken", she had been rescued from human traffickers by her estranged father Bryan. And it wouldn't have been unreasonable for her to be severely traumatized by her experiences in that earlier film. But the Mills family are "amicably separated" and little Kimmie is about to take her driver's test, as well as dating a boy who Daddy's not sure he approves of. But while the three are tourists in Istanbul, the father of the human trafficker who Bryan killed in the process of revenge for Kim's abduction has just buried his son in Albania and now wants to show Bryan that "payback is a moyobets"--or however you render it in Albanian. Papa and his remaining sons catch up to Bryan and his ex while they're out shopping, with Kim deliberately back at the hotel so as to "re-matchmake" Mom and Dad. Bryan knows that some sort of attempt may also be made on Kim so he calls her to tell her to take preventative measures. Too late--she's already managed to elude attackers there and now proceeds to dash to Mom and Dad's rescue, coached by Bryan over the phone. Running across rooftops and throwing grenades every which way. At one point during the high-speed chase after reaching Bryan, Kim is the driver so Dad can shoot back at pursuers. These scenes turn out to be how the action adventure genre might approach the "Daddy's Girl" phenomenon. It's almost anticlimactic in the final scenes when the girl actually takes the driver's test back home. The DMV examiner thankfully doesn't know that this particular "applicant" has recently roared all over Istanbul like she was Steve McQueen's daughter in a "borrowed" Mercedes taxicab.

reviewText: Taken 2(released Sept/12) stars Liam Neeson as Bryan Mills,Maggie Grace as Kim Mills,Famke Janssen as Lenore, and others.Neeson is back in his role,from the first film,as a retired special agent with "many skills".The action,when it roles,is fast and furious and the production team makes good use of the booming bass lines and noise emphasis that has become so popular in films these past few years,to "enhance" the on screen action.I have a problem with this film,but let's get into the plot first.The story has us all reunited with the Mills family in L.A.,and this time around there are two converging plots.One is that Neeson's ex is having problems with her new beau and his daughter is trying to get out of taking her driving test that she and daddy have been working on for some time.We switch over to a funeral in Albania where the father,a crime boss,and father of one o the kiddnappers from the first film,is laying to rest his son along with the others Neeson killed the first go round.The father wants revenge and revenge he shall get.Back in L.A.Neeson is off to Istanbul,Turkey to provide security for a wealthy Arab sheik.He had asked his ex and daughter to come along,but not hearing anything,flew over alone.He is surprised,once his work is done,to have them walk in on him in the hotel lobby.About 30 minutes into the film the Albanians follow and finally kidnap both Neeson and his wife.His daughter is back at the hotel in the swimming area.The couple have hoods over their heads in the kidnap van,but the ever vigilant Neeson counts the miles and keeps track of sounds he hears.They arrive at kidnap central and the wife is cut on the neck and turned upside down in chains to bleed to death,while Neeson,shackled,has to watch.Neeson has a small phone hidden and manages to call his daughter to tell her what has happened and to get to her fathers hotel room a.s.a.p..The kidnappers come but don't find her.Neeson and daughter reconnect and Neeson has his daughter plotting points on a map and throwing grenades to see how fast the sound reaches Neeson's ears.In short order his daughter has a fix on dad and finds the very chimney that falls down into his room.Neeson has meanwhile freed his wife and the gun his daughter throws down provides him with some defense.His daughter gets chased over rooftops by the kidnappers while Neeson leaves his wife to help his daughter.This he does and both commandeer a cab and return to the kidnap location.Neeson goes in but his wife has been taken away.Neeson and daughter are chased through the narrow Istanbul streets until they are able to reach the U.S.Embassy there and safety.Neeson leaves his daughter to return to find his wife.Neeson retraces his original trip in the van and finds kidnap central where his wife is.He fights his way in,finds his wife and leaves her once more to get to the leader.Neeson gives the man a choice to stop following he and his family,or otherwise be killed.When the man nods in agreement he drops his gun and the man picks the gun up and fires an empty gun at him.Neeson had of course taken the last bullet out.Neeson dispatches the father tout suite.The film ends with the family enjoying a dinner on,what looks suspiciously like,the Malibu Sports Fishing Pier.The film certainly has a lot of action to it and Neeson is stone cold,smart and calculating as before.However the prerequisite for an action film is believability.The first one had it in spades,that's why it was so good.This one had some disturbing lapses that had me mentally saying "c'mon,you just didn't do that?".One moment is when Neeson's daughter is fleeing their hotel and she goes straight to the basement,like she knows where she's going,she enters an employee locker area,opens one up and puts on the clothes inside(as to blend in) and leaves.I have never seen a better FITTING ensemble than she had on when leaving.That was NOT believable.Another issue is that of Neeson's daughter and her lack of driving license.It is assumed that she and her dad had been practicing for months in his car,but she had avoided getting her license.To top that knowing that most of the cars in California are automatics,it boggles the mind to watch her drive the stolen cab in narrow Istanbul streets like she was a pro,AND uses a stick shift,which she,at least as far as we know,knows nothing about!!?? Then there is the matter of Neeson's wife and her kidnapping.The fact that Neeson left her once to help his daughter is bad enough,but leaving her again is just so out of Neeson's character as to be totally unbelievable.It is funny that I bring this up because this DVD has an alternate ending to it,which I prefer.In it Neeson doesn't leave his wife the second time.In that version instead Neeson,after having helped his daughter and having returned to kidnap central to fetch his wife,he does indeed come back with her and all of them flee to the U.S.embassy instead of just Neeson and daughter in the theatrical version.The director has a comment before you watch the alternate ending that he preferred the theatrical cut,but thought this alternate provided better entertainment.Well I think he blew it.The alternate ending is the most believable and is most in keeping with Neeson's character.I could have maybe somewhat overlooked the daughter's cloths wearing and her pro like driving skills with a manual shift,but when the lead character does something that is so totally out of line with what he should normally be expected to do,especially a character like his that is so detailed oriented,then sorry I cannot buy into it.Technically speaking the film is in its w/s a/r of 2:35:1 and is clear and crisp.Extras include that alternate ending I told you about and an interview with Neeson on his promotional junket for the film.All in all,though the film has its good action moments and Neeson is in top form in his character,the film falters because of the producers letting the aforementioned incidents of unbelievability sneak into the film.I cannot fathom why the director,if they really KNEW the character of Bryan Mills,would they prefer a version that clearly goes against type? For the good of the film's integrity,the theatrical version's ending should have been the alternate,not the other way around.

reviewText: Crammed full of relentless, nonstop action, even more so than the first installment, "Taken 2" is loads of fun, with excellent direction by Luc Besson, and Liam Neeson once again in top fighting shape.  The Albanians whose sons were murdered by Leeson in "Taken" are out for revenge, and they corner Leeson and his family in Istanbul. What follows are wild blazing car chases through narrow streets and bazaars, with car-to-car shootouts, pileups and crashes, countless well-choreographed karate chop-chop martial arts battles between Neeson and the thugs, pop-pop shootings, stabbings and garrotings, and torture scenes.  It is extremely formulaic, very much a cutout of the original, but you can't help cheering for Neeson when he commands his daughter -- "stay focused" -- and proceeds to kick, shoot and flail his way through legions of surly-looking Albanian thugs, emerging remarkably unblemished.  Apparently the chief thug still has a couple of sons unaccounted for, which leaves the door open for a sequel.  I say, go for it.  Excellent, absolutely first-rate production values and nice performances by all.
summary: Fast and furious fighting Albanians, with Neeson giving them all they can handle

reviewText: yeah it is possible to to find ones kidnapped daughter but not likely. Even for an experienced agent.  Is it possible to be shot at with automatic weapons on full fire without taking several wounds?  No. Is it possible to fire an automatic weapon on full fire for more than a few seconds?  No. At a rate of fire in the hundreds of rounds per minute, one would be forever reloading. and generally it is a waste of ammo. Plus one would be a walking armory of extra clips. Today's movies show our heroes getting shot sometimes but then arising after a day or two and continuing action. Highly unlikely. Two movies come to mind that portray a more realistic scenario. The Swedish version of The Girl who Kicked the Hornets nest.  Our heroine is out of commission for weeks after being shot three times. That she was able to get up for a few minutes to exact revenge is a testament to the strength of will power after which she collapses again. The movie, Safe House, shows people being realistically wounded and shot to death. With real sounding guns including a "silenced" rifle. Bullets still break the sound barrier thus creating the noise. Yeah this is nitpicking. But I prefer the more realistic to the merely theatrical.

reviewText: I have not been able to get to the theater for taken two and after seeing the Blu-ray with theatrical version, unrated version, and an alternate version, I'm kind of glad that I did not get to see the theatrical version first. The unrated cut in taken 2 is again living proof that the unrated version is the gold standard; I've yet to see any exception to that rule. As the basic blurb on the film synopsis indicates, the turnaround is that the parents get taken. The big difference in approximately the latter third of the film is that it takes an entirely different ambit to the theatrical cut (and I can honestly say that I can't see why they did the theatrical cut the way they did, but there is enough in the film extras if you to make up your own mind). Without giving too much away, they might have called this taken 2; the revenge: however it's more of a vendetta type of situation and I like the way the film has a fairly good précis of the characters (on both sides) so you can see who has what motivation, and who were the ones that you are going to side with (obviously you are meant to side with Bryan Mills and his family). If you liked TAKEN ONE As Well as  Liam's film UNKNOWN, then I think you will really like the action, adventure, and exploration of a great deal of motivation in the agents.There is an alternative ending they supplied, which gives a radical change to the general feel of the film: it's about 25 minutes of fully complete material and has a radically different run in the motivation and action to the extent that you might even be able to get three films out of the entire material. There are five major deleted scenes in the extras, of which the foot chase is the longest and actually provides a lot of intriguing background, in my view. In one of two bonus materials there is a small discussion with Liam Neeson and it really gets into his motivation in the film (not necessarily his character's) as well as the way he works and what he likes about films; it's very enlightening. The final neat bonus is an in-depth animatic of the black ops box (the silver case he takes everywhere) and it is fairly obvious that is very well thought out. Overall, I was not sure if I was going to enjoy this film, due to a lot of negative reviews, but after watching the original TAKEN in saying the somewhat more thoughtful film UNKNOWN (which is based on a book, a spy thriller) I was willing to give TAKEN 2 a try, and I'm glad I did. It's a whacking great ride and loads of fun.
summary: Action for the plus size film

reviewText: The unrated cut runs about 6 minutes longer.  It's definitely a harder cut than the theatrical version, but nothing R-rated.  I'm primarily interested in the storyline differences between the theatrical cut and the unrated cut, so SPOILERS follow below.  Do not read further if you do not want to be spoiled!1) Makeout scene between Jamie and Kim is longer, nothing explicit, but Kim is unsure about going further physically with Jamie.2) Bryan calls Sam to have him perform a routine background search on Jamie.3) The interrogation of Jean Claude is a little more brutal and Murad's chief henchman, Suko (stunt coordinator Alain Figlarz), reveals that one of the deceased in the first movie was his brother.4) Before Bryan takes his daughter on the fireworks boat cruise, they briefly hit up a dance club first where Kim does a little dancing.5) After Bryan escapes from his imprisonment and fights Murad's men watching the soccer game, he stabs a man in the throat with his empty gun.  This is pretty brutal.6) After Bryan shoots Boris who falls to his death with a finger on the trigger, Bryan is attacked by a second henchman who meets the same fate and lands on top of Boris's corpse.7) Extra shots of Bryan skulking around Murad's hideout looking for Lenore.8) Additional scenes of Bryan chasing Murad, Suko, and Lenore through the streets of Istanbul.9) The final fight scene between Bryan and Suko is about twice as long as the theatrical version.  Suko cuts Bryan on the palm with his hidden knife.10) Most, if not all, of the fist fights between Bryan and the henchmen are longer and more brutal.11) Additional sound effects, e.g. throat gurgling, neck breakings, etc.., have been re-inserted.12) Most, if not all, action scenes involving people dying by firearms feature extra rounds fired into the victims.I enjoyed Taken 2.  Sure, some parts may have been MacGyver-ish, but it's always entertaining to see Liam Neeson beat up henchmen.  WSD, people.  Willing Suspension of Disbelief.  At least the hand-to-hand action scenes were better cut than the Bourne series.
summary: Taken 2 Unrated Cut vs. Theatrical Cut Storyline Differences

reviewText: On first inspection it would seem that Luc Besson runs a factory these days that dispenses one action movie after another. He has a stable of directors, cameramen, composers, editors, etc. that go from one product to another. there is a lack of imagination these days coming from the man behind the Fifth Element and the Professional, two great films that were more than a decade ago.Besson's latest director to hand films off to for assembly seems to be one Olivier Megatron, who helmed the mundane Transporter 3 and last year's excruciatingly dull Columbiana. To say that Taken 2 is his best effort so far isn't as much of a compliment as it sounds, it's more like stating a fact with little zeal.Taking place soon after the events of 2008's Taken, this time around the retired splenetic CIA man Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson) is vacating in Istanbul, Turkey when his daughter, Kim (Maggie Grace) and ex-wife, Lenore (Famke Janssen), pull a surprise appearance. At the same time, the family of the cast of villains from the first movie come looking for some settling of scores. The new crop of Albanian heavies are led by Murad (Rade Serbedzja), the father of one of Neeson's targets the first time around.Mills and Lenore are taken hostage, while Kim searches for them. A sort of reversal of events from the last time around. Eventually, Mills escapes with his daughter's help and some handy grenades. He plots his own mission of ruthless revenge and retribution.Like it's predecessor, there is a lot of slick action here, everything is fairly neat and tidy, probably too much so. The action sequences are well staged, but there is an over emphasis on quick cut editing to assist the 60 year-old Nesson get through his physical work, that leaves the audience a little nauseated and dazed. Suspense is built through the menacing score by Nathanel Mechaly and the chases scenes are enhanced by solid editing. The camerawork from Besson regular Romain Lacourbas is decent, but workman like. They are also enough car crashes her to make Burt Reynolds salivate. I guess the anonymous stunt drivers should get some credit, good job guys.Once again the whole show really is Liam Neeson, an actor too good for this sort of material which he seems to do a lot of now, but he adds dignity and enhances what is essentially a 21st century Charles Bronson role. He works his way through some awkward situations and recycled dialogue from the first movie, but handles it with class that makes this more a pleasure to watch than it really deserves to be. Neeson, should get some better roles soon though, if he wishes to avoid following Nicolas Cage's poor example.Maggie Grace is unfortunately just too old for this role, she was too old the first time around, here she is really too old, like Channing Tatum-Jonah Hill too old. She's supposed to still be in high school and studying for her driving exam, but looks to be in her mid twenties. I usually don't complain about such things, except in cases like this where it becomes distracting. She also seems a little more awkward with her acting than before, perhaps because her character is so underwritten that she comes across as a little less than a half-wit.And poor Rade Serbedzja, a Serbian leading man and a fine actor, who is sadly given very little to do in a movie such as this. Much like the first go around, Taken 2 suffers from the lack of a strong central villain. There are plenty of anonymous badies for Neeson to off, but no one to create a real lasting impression. Action and thrillers are often made by a strong antagonist, think how James Bond movies are often defined by their villains.Famke Janssen, like last time, is again strictly window dressing.Megatron would appear to be the least of the filmmakers working in the Besson group these days, which makes it rather peculiar that he would place such an important title as Taken 2 in his clearly incapable hands. At least Pierre Morel, director of the previous movie had reasonably impressive skills at storytelling and greater strength in his dynamics.The script written by Besson and his frequent collaborator Robert Mark Karmen, who also wrote the first movie, is nothing to great either. Plodding and rehashing the original film a whole lot, when they aren't reusing situations and even dialogue, they at times resort to flashbacks.Overtly stylish like it's popular, but somewhat overrated predecessor, the Taken movies aim for a macho toughness like action pics of the past, but allow themselves to be undone by their anemic bloodletting and safe for mass consumption PG-13 violence, even in the unrated version. These movies lack the edge that it so desperately desires.Yet, at a well paced and reasonable length of ninety-two minutes, everything moves at a fast enough pace to forgive much of it's short comings, which there are many.  Taken 2 fails to make us care much about the characters or events on screen, but keeps us reasonable entertain none the less. But let it be known that where the first movie was an old song played at a different tempo, this time around it's strictly a cover version.Check out my reviews at moviezonemagazine.com

reviewText: "Taken" was, I believe the first attempt to transform Liam Neeson into a macho action hero, and I suppose it succeeded, but it also transformed him into a truly dull person. The first film was ham-handed, unbelievable, and also pretty unappetizing,with its "white-slavery" plot underpinning. But, as with anything Luc-Besson-related, it's all about the kinetic action.  And that's fine, if the director brings something to it. He doesn't, and the mawkish Hallmark family stuff just dumbs it down further."Taken 2" concerns itself even less with plot... it's just a relentless revenge tale, also clumsily directed.  In terms of believability, it makes any "Die Hard" movie look like a documentary.  I realize these movies are not about realism at all, but the car-chase scene, where the daughter (who failed her driving test 3 times) goes all Steve McQueen on the tiny twisty Istanbul streets, is ridiculous, and if the director was attempting to be ironic, he failed miserably.I think the worst thing, aside from the fact that no one in the film is at all likeable or remotely interesting, the film is totally devoid of humor. Suspense, thrills and humor CAN co-exist.  (witness: "Die Hard"....the first one only!!)I DID actually watch both movies, got 'em from my library.  They were good for practicing bass guitar, not much to think about, bouncy, relentless soundtrack. So, really, just an aerobics video.Other than that, you could do MUCH better. So could Liam. But I guess at this point he's just collecting paychecks.
summary: Dumber than the First, but Actually More Watchable

reviewText: Spoilers lie below.Like: Brian Mills isn't super human, we see him actually look like he's struggling in some of the fight scenes. Liam Neeson mentioned in an interview that he didn't want to do the film if it lacked this element since it wouldn't make sense for Brian Mills to take a beating and be perfectly fine at his age. Kudos for this.Dislike: Cheesy. Mills and his wife get back together. Some of the mushy dialogue. Yuck.Like: The daughter (who's name escapes me as I type this) serves a purpose.Dislike: The daughter is still whiny and immature. Listen to your flippin' father! He saved your butt so he obviously knows what he's doing!Like: The idea of revenge. You can't kill a bunch of people and not anger someone.Dislike: The villain is an old man... Okay, bonus points for making Liam Neeson have to face someone in his age bracket and for mirroring the situation Mills went through in the first film (loss of child). However, it's almost pathetic... maybe it should've been an uncle? Brother? Brother-in-law? ....anything other than the father of one of the people he killed in Taken.Like: The fact that there is this gray area of morality brought up by having Mills face the father of someone he killed. Why was his daughter's life worth killing so many people? Shouldn't he face some sort of punishment for his actions? Even if they were bad men, he still took the law into his own hands and killed them.... When there's a gray area like that it makes the film more interesting regardless of what side of the gray area your opinions lie.Dislike: You set off how many grenades in Istanbul and no one noticed? The city didn't shut down for potential terrorist activity? Huh? Not believable at all.Overall I decent film, worth watching. Not the best action film ever though... and the original was much better.
summary: Not as good as the first film

reviewText: I knew nothing about Taken when it was released in 2008, but it proved to be one of the best action movies I had ever seen. There was just enough information about the characters to care about them, and the action was intense and rather elegant.That shouldn't surprise me because Luc Besson and Robert Mark Kamen wrote the script. Besson had previously grabbed my attention with Léon: The Professional, which is one of the best action movies ever made. La Femme Nikita was another notable triumph. I mention all that to explain why I was already sold on the idea of Taken 2 as soon as it was announced.So, did it meet my lofty expectations?The opening scenes were something of a surprise with Brian Mills (Neeson) interacting with his ex-wife, Lenore (Janssen), and daughter, Kim (Grace) extensively. I like that we are shown how Mills has grown closer to Lenore. In the original movie, she was cold and spiteful, but the two are clearly on better terms now that Mills has used his skills to rescue Kim from her kidnappers. It made perfect sense and rang true for me.The plot is simple. If you remember Marko from the first movie, you'll probably know that he was part of an Albanian gang. In Taken 2, Marko's father is obsessed with avenging the death of his son. He's not interested in why Marko was killed, or that he was guilty of many crimes, he's only interested in seeing Mills killed. When Mills takes Lenore and Kim on vacation to Istanbul, Marko's father instructs his gang to capture Mills and his family. He partly succeeds, but Kim escapes.The opening setup is quite long and thorough, and I remember thinking that more than half the audience were probably anxious to see Neeson get on with the task of eliminating the opposition in as many unique and violent ways as possible. However, once the action starts, it's relentless and intense. We see car chases, shootouts, fights, threats, brief torture, and a rapidly increasing body count.Mills wants Kim to stay out of danger, but eventually enlists her help. I'm half expecting a sequel called 'Miss Taken.'It's unrealistic to expect a movie of this nature to be completely plausible. After all, the basic premise is that a 60-year-old man is capable of defeating gangs armed with automatic weapons. The method Mills uses to escape his kidnappers is so simple that I have to wonder why he didn't do it about 30 minutes earlier, but I'll forgive that.The ending was quite inventive, and paves the way for another sequel should Neeson and the cast want to reprise their roles a third time.I did have a few minor complaints, such as the kidnappers talking in English when it's obvious that they would stick to Albanian. Another minor annoyance was the use of shaky cam shots throughout most of the intense action scenes. There's a fine line between adding excitement and losing track of the events on the screen. The line was crossed a few times.Overall, I was happy with Taken 2. It delivered more of what I liked about the first movie and added depth to the relationships between the main characters. I don't think it's quite as good as Taken because we now know what Mills is capable of, and some of the pleasure of the first movie was seeing Mills demonstrate his unique set of skills for the first time.Taken 2 definitely works better if you have seen the first installment. Some of the actions and dialogue are direct references to events from the first movie, and you will miss some of the humor if you aren't aware of past events.Fans of Taken will be more than happy with this worthy sequel.Two things to remember:1) Never agree to go on vacation with Brian Mills.2) If Neeson uses your taxi cab, you probably won't see it in one piece again.
summary: A worthy sequel, without quite matching the original installment

reviewText: POSSIBLE SPOILERS FOLLOWOk, Taken was a great action movie.  It was fresh, it was action packed, and it starred a formidable character, the former CIA Agent Bryan Mills.  While the sequel isn't as good (very few sequels are), it's good at what it's meant for - a vicious, unrelenting action/revenge movie.Bryan Mills has just finished an assignment in Istanbul, when his ex-wife Lenore (who's having marriage problems with her current rich husband) and his daughter Kim, surprise him at the hotel.  The movie gets crazy quick, as family members from the slain Albanians from the first film attempt to snatch all three.  They succeed with Bryan and Lenore but fail to snatch Kim, due to a call from Bryan.Through guiding Kim, Bryan is able to help her aid in his escape, fight his way through bad guys, and so the movie goes.  It culminates after an hour of fist-fights and more gunplay with a great Krav Maga-style fight between Bryan Mills and the right-hand man of Murad, the Albanian Mob Boss.  Bryan then confronts and kills Murad, and leaves with Lenore to rejoin Kim.For plot, the movie feels less effective than its predecessor, but for action, it is well-paced and enough to serve its purpose as an action movie.

reviewText: The one man demolition machine that is Brian Mills is at it again: killing people with impunity; this time on the streets of Istanbul. Basically, the family patriarch back in the old country, Albania, finishes burying what remains of the scumbags Brian wiped out in Paris, and vows revenge. He seems to be some kind of mafia godfather who has the usual connections in high places. He quickly finds Brian's location, on a long weekend with `Lenny', his ex-wife and Kim, his once airheaded daughter, in Istanbul, where Brian's just finished protecting the family of some uber rich oil sheik or similar, and starts off to find him with a second cohort of equally nasty scumbags in tow.Having bribed his way through typically corrupt officials high and low the patriarch sets up camp in what looks like a deserted and run down Istanbul apartment. The apartment block itself looked to be in a very similar part of town to that which both Tom Cruise, in Night and Day, and Clive Owen, in the International, visited. Obviously, the roof tops of old Istanbul provide a good location in which to shoot the odd roof top set piece.Anyway, having located his prey said patriarch and minions duly `take' Brian and Lenny, in order to fulfil his and the film's mission and truss them up with chains and such like in what looks like the apartment block's basement. Then, being conveniently incompetent, leave them alone with a conveniently incompetent sleepy headed scumbag guard outside. Kim, who, during the film's opening, had received a driving lesson from Brian back in LA, has managed to avoid being captured, by stealing a taxi, and also manages to retrieve Brian's mini arsenal of assault weapons. Brian gives her instructions - yeh, they are able to communicate; I won't say how - and sets about enabling Brian to let her home in on his exact location!Kim duly retrieves Brian and, now performing like a seasoned rally driver, picks him up at the start of the obligatory car chase through the old streets and alley ways of Istanbul.Obviously, I can't say how this all turns out but I'm sure you can guess! It's nowhere nearly as good as Brian's first outing and does contain a similar number of sizeable plot holes but does provide some action-packed entertainment, albeit a bit too predictably and we do get to see the rooftops of Istanbul once more!Here's looking forward to Taken 3 the inevitability of which is set up quite nicely at the end!
summary: Brian Mills – on the rampage again!

reviewText: I saw it in the local DVD rental and was attracted to it the way one is attracted to the scene of an accident. Could it be any worse than its predecessor? The short answer is, yes. A plot of staggering weakness and sublime silliness, varying wildly between maudlin sloppiness and utter mayhem, with holes sufficiently large to swallow an entire depot of London buses, laughable acting and the consumption of more ammunition than was used on D-Day. Now if you like fairy stories of the good guys coming out on top with barely a scratch and having massacred an entire battalion of nasties, then this is for you, but otherwise I'd recommend that you avoid.The worrying thing is that there is left hanging in the plot the possibility of a "Taken 3"... Given the enthusiasm of other reviewers, this could be a done deal.

Armed with a cell phone with a Turkish SIM card, a shoe lace, and some government issue grenades, Kim goes McGyver on them to save the family.Definitely lacks the intensity of the first film. I would wait to watch this one cheap.Parental Guide: No f-bombs, sex, or nudity.

reviewText: "We will find him. We will bring him here. We will not rest until his blood flows into this very ground. We will have our revenge." After his daughter (Grace) was taken and he went through hell to get her back Bryan Mills (Neeson) made a pact to be a more involved father. reviewText: Taken 2 suffers from the typical movie sequel cliché, the second one is not as good as the first.  Both movies followed exactly the same formula: villain kidnaps family of the hero, car chases ensue, body count mounts, hero kills head honcho villain in a climatic confrontation, hero and family live happily ever after.But while Taken was a fantastic movie and had me on the edge of my seat the whole time, Taken 2 was kinda ho-hum.  I had two big issues with the plot:  1) The whole kidnapping, chase, and rescue scenario was so far-fetched  that it was almost laughable.  2) The villain was made to look too "human".  In the first scene of Take 2 the villain (a gray-haired old man) is shown burying his son and other family members and vowing revenge against his son's killer.  In a different movie this story line would have made this man the hero.  This setup just made the old man look like less of an evil psychopath (like the villain in the first movie) and more like a grieving father bent on revenge.The things that saved this movie were the great acting and the beautiful location.
summary: The sequel is never as good as the original

reviewText: How do you come back from the worst experience in your life? Therapy, denial, maybe some substance abuse? What if, after a relatively short amount of time, you're flung back into a very similar circumstance? I don't imagine that would help.Sometime after returning to the relative safety of Los Angeles, Bryan Mills (played by Liam Neeson), his ex-wife Lenore (played by Famke Janssen) and their daughter Kim (played by Maggie Grace) are still rebounding from the trauma they suffered. Bryan (Neeson) arrives at Kim's home to give her a driving lesson only to be informed that she is not even in the house. She's with her boyfriend. A boyfriend Bryan knew nothing about, no less. Simultaneously, in Tropoje, Albania, Murad Hoxha, father of deceased kidnapper and human trafficker Marko Hoxha, is attending a funeral service being conducted for his son and his accomplices. Murad (played by Rade Serbedzija) vows to avenge the deaths of his son and his friends. After hearing that a planned vacation to China is cancelled by Lenore's now estranged husband, Bryan invites both Kim and Lenore to join him on a business trip in Istanbul once he's fulfilled his professional obligations. They arrive sooner than expected and, unbeknownst to them, followed by Murad's henchman. Following a family lunch in the marketplace, Kim returns to the hotel. It's immediately apparent to Bryan and Lenore that their daughter hopes privacy and the exotic locale will rekindle feelings of love in her long-divorced parents. While romance does seem to be in bloom between the couple, it is abruptly halted when Murad and his men make their play for the Mills family.Now, I was and still am a huge fan of the 2008 film. I believe Neeson took a film that would've seemed dull and uninspired in the hands of Jason Statham, Vin Diesel, or any other contemporary action star and elevated it beyond the material. This film, while entertaining and plausible enough for an action/adventure, is the lesser of the two. Of course, there's the fact that it's more of the same and, therefore, less interesting. In addition, while the original depended on Neeson's estimable talent, this film relies heavily on Maggie Grace. A competent actress, sure, but nowhere near as good as Liam Neeson. I enjoyed it about as much as I expected to. That's it.

reviewText: What is the point of making a sequel to a film when there is very little potential left for developing the concept of the original? A retired CIA agent Bryan Mills is back and Liam Neeson once again brings gravitas to the role that made him an action star about four years ago, but the script of "Taken 2" (written by Luc Besson and his long-time collaborator Robert Mark Kamen) looks more like a reenactment of the original's story set in a more exotic Istanbul location and seen from a different viewpoint.The story is simple. Bryan Mills (Liam Neeson) is on business trip in Istanbul, where he is reunited with his ex-wife Lenore (Famke Janssen) and daughter Kim (Maggie Grace). Then a band of vengeful Albanian gangsters led by Murad (Rade Sherbedgia) arrives with guns, to avenge the deaths of the men that Mills killed in "Taken."Now I am not saying that "Taken 2" is a bad movie. The film is slick and action-packed, though action sequences tend to be less credible and thrilling because of choppy editing and our familiarity with the story. As the original's freshness and novelty is gone, the sequel (that looks more like a remake) is more predictable, treading on familiar paths and not veering into new territory, except when Neeson's character is given a rare moment to show his vulnerability.After all, if there is one reason you should see "Taken 2," it is Liam Neeson showing what a talented actor like him really can do. You know exactly where the story is going, and what his character will do, but at least he does it effectively.
summary: Looks More Like a Remake Than a Sequel

reviewText: The original Taken was an incredible movie, and Taken 2 has got some incredible moments. The main difference is that Bryan Mill's (Liam Neeson) family plays a much larger role in the sequel. While the first movie is about a lone wolf taking out bad guys like gnats on a summer day to get his daughter back, this one involves the family unit, so the experience, while using incredible action scenes, is a bit different.There is also a little more down time in this film, as cheesy tender moments are used to work the audience up before mother and father are abducted by a psychotic terrorist hellbent on getting revenge as a result of Bryan killing his son.This film provides tons of kills, explosions and everything else that makes a movie good, and it has some real cheese in it, leading up to the action you're wanting. I say go see this film. I didn't enjoy it as much as the first one because I'd rather see Bryan go it alone, but this is still a great action film. I liked it enough to want there to be a third installment.As for the cheese in the film, the script is pretty bad, especially the dialogue between father and daughter, father and ex-wife before the movie gets rolling, but Liam Neeson is a great actor, so he saves it from veering off to Dolph Lundgren or Steven Segal territory (Hey, I'm not saying their movies are bad, just saying the dialogue is).Anyway, if you love action and like family films, this is the one for you, brother.
summary: For the Action Man and Family Man

reviewText: I had heard horrible things about "Taken 2" and reluctantly rented it when there wasn't anything else that interested me. While not quite as good as the first film which blew on the scene somewhat unexpectantly, "Taken 2" still manages to be breezy entertainment with Liam Neeson dong what he does best in action films--beating the bad guys at their own game.SPOILERS:While in Istanbul ex-CIA agent Bryan Mills (Neeson), his ex-wife (Famke Janssen--somebody give this underrated actress another film with some substance--please!) are kidnapped by the father (Rade Serbedzija)of one of the men he killed in the first movie. Mills must rely on his daughter Kim (Maggie Grace who, at 27, is getting a wee bit too old for these roles)to help him escape and rescue his wife.END OF SPOILERS:"Taken 2" certainly doesn't break any new ground and it's not the unexpected back-to-basics thriller that the first one was but it's enjoyable on its own terms. The action sequences are well directed although this film, unlike the first, seems a bit like all the other recent action thrillers released in terms of staging and stunts. The editing is a bit more choatic, again, much like most of the other action films we've seen over the last decade and while does a adequate job, he lacks the flair of Pierre Morel who made the first film.Having said that, it is tough to direct a sequel to a popular film like "Taken" because the expectations the first film (which came as a bit of a surprise to many) aren't there. "Taken 2" is still fun particularly as a mindless way to spent a rainy afternoon or if you're at home sick.The blu-ray looks particularly nice particularly some of the beautifully shot establishing shots of L.A. and Istanbul. Detail is abundant and there's quite a bit of detail evident in this crisp presentation of the film.The audio is equally impressive with a nice, immersive soundtrack with dialogue STILL remaining clear. We get a variety of subtitles for the film including English, Spanish and, of all things, Mandarin.The special features includes a "Black Ops Field Manual" (this is only available on the unrated version) which acts as a clever pop up option with background info on the film.We also get deleted scenes and alternate ending that provides an interesting, slightly different taste to the conclusion of the film.We can also browse through Mills' weapons case and learn about each one."In Character with Liam Neeson" is from FX Movie Channel and is a fluff piece where the actor discusses his character.We also get the theatrical trailer and, for those using BD Live, Fox gives them an exclusive making of featurette which I didn't watch.Is "Taken 2" a worthwhile investment to buy? That depends on how much of a fan of this film you are. It certainly is entertaining and engaging.If you're in doubt perhaps a rental would be the first best choice. I know I might pick this up when the price drops just because I enjoy Neeson's performance as Mills and it really is a fun action thriller.
summary: Not as taken with the second film but it's still entertaining with a solid performance from Neeson.

reviewText: Despite being a pretty darn good overall movie in its own right, the original "Taken" succeeds primarily because Liam Neeson makes the leap from solid character actor to leading man.  His performance is what carries the show.  In this sequel, the filmmakers are able to replicate pretty much the same scenarios as that original and get away with it because of the raw emotion involved in both the stories and the characters.For a basic plot summary, "Taken 2" sees the same gang that abducted Kim (Maggie Grace) in the first movie now looking for revenge against parents Brian (Neeson) and Lenore (Famke Janssen).There are two reasons why this film works so well despite using much of the same subject matter as the original:1. The emotions behind the simple revenge-based plot are so visceral.  Grace's persona of Kim is so innocent (but yet true-to-life) that one cannot help but root for her either to be the hero or the one being saved by the hero.  Simply put, she's the on-screen daughter that everyone wants to protect.2. With that first crucial plot step in place, Neeson's magnificent character is given a chance to shine.  With Grace providing the dramatic moments, Neeson brings the action and intensity with a passion.  Film buffs recently learned that Neeson's distinctive baritone means nothing without a great plot/drama behind it (see: "Unknown").  When given the opportunity to hone his character, though, Neeson can provide relentless intensity with as little as a few words.Overall, "Taken 2" is a strong sequel to the original.  It pretty much contains all the "same stuff" as the first one, but the characters are still relatable and the action is still top-notch.  If you really enjoyed "Taken", this will probably not be a disappointment for you.
summary: A Rare Feat Of Successful Repetition

reviewText: Basically, this is a decent action movie.  Nothing more.  The story is basic.  Nothing interesting or thrilling.  Taken was spectacular.  I think the reason this movie is not that great is that the daughter and wife get in the way.  We want to see Liam's character do what he does best.  There are not enough fights in this film.  Instead he needs his civilian daughter's help.  Boring.In fact, the plot falls flat in a few really silly and fundamental ways.He invites his family (ex-wife included) to a place we all know today is a Muslim trouble zone just waiting to become a launching pad for terrorists.  Why would a wise black ops operative do that?  Silly.  Unless, like most divorced men and women, he was secretly hoping his ex would get captured.  But then that would make this a comedy.Also, he has all these interesting friends with histories akin to his own, but they NEVER get used!  Why are you showing us his friends??? (Who are played by some really talented actors, by the way).  What a waste of some neat teamwork scenes or innovative spy-in-the-field scenes.Also, why the hell are we subjected to his daughter's boyfriend?  What plot purpose does he serve?  Don't waste my time.Lastly, the guys he fights are not very spectacular.  Just a bunch of street bums and thugs really.  Wouldn't it have been interesting if the Chinese or Russians had stepped in to cause a little trouble for an American agent who has evaded them on their own soil and made them look foolish in spy operations of the past?  Maybe some special agents to help out the kidnappers and give Liam's character some real opponents?  As it is, his toughest fight is against a short squat guy who looks like he makes pizza in Hoboken, New Jersey.  And his vanquishing of the main evil antagonist was literally as easy as hanging a coat in a coat closet.  You'll understand when you see it.The film would have been much better if Liam had been forced to deal with the Mexican cartels who kidnap innocents from America even as we speak.  Leave his family at home.  They appeared in the first movie and that was all we needed to see of them.  Give us some interesting plot twists that involve the the dirty underground of spies and internation criminals or something.  Not a silly vacation gone bad.  Frankly I think if he had lost his traveler's checks and had to search the hotel for them, watching that would have been more entertaining than a few of the scenes that did not make the cutting room floor.Taken 3 please!  Revitalize this character.  Bring in his friends.  Kill off his annoying family.

reviewText: This film is a sequel to Taken and like most sequels (except for the Goodfather) is not as good as the first movie. Surprisingly, it has nothing to do with the acting or the story but with the direction.The plot is simple and happens in Istanbul. The father of Marco from Tropoa wants revenge. He puts together a band of thugs from his third world country and comes to Istanbul where he has access to everything: from the government officials to the police (people in third world countries help each other...). Byan Milles (Liam Neesom) is vacationing in Istanbul with his ex-wife and daughter. His ex-wife just got separated from her husband.The movie had potential and the acting of all participants is really outstanding. However, the direction is really terrible. The fight scenes are really well done but the views from one cameras to the other are multiple and unnecessary. I don't know who did the final cut of the movie, but the person is totally incompetent. And that started with the opening titles, when the bodies are flown to Albania. There are so many camera angles/changes that make you really dizzy. At first I said, OK this it is an exception, poorly done but just the beginning, it will get better. Absolutely not! During the first fight in the market, just before he is taken, I had to close my eyes several times and look away because it made me dizzy and I wanted to puke.  I am not sure who decided to have 20-30 cameras for one fight and have an angle shown from each one at least once, but that was a bad idea; it is a total failure. I have seen Colombiana which was directed by Olivier Megaton and I know Luc Besson was involved in the making of the movie. Never had any problems with Colombiana and I have seen several movies by Luc Besson (the Big Blue, the Fifth Element) and was really happy with his plot and direction. I was really surprised by these deficiencies in this movie.Zero stars for the direction, five stars for the acting and four stars for the script. Overall three stars.Taken 3 is in the works. Hopefully they will choose another director. Please...
summary: How a director can destroy a good script and great acting!
